 livre du mois|isbn=978-2-7028-3581-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Randi|first=James|authorlink=James Randi|title=The mask of Nostradamus|url=https://archive.org/details/maskofnostradamu00jame|url-access=registration|date=1 September 1990|publisher=Scribner|isbn=978-0-684-19056-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rollet|first=Pierre|title=Interpr\u00e9tation des hi\u00e9roglyphes de Horapollo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2Xr4tgAACAAJ|year=1993|publisher=M. Petit|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Watts|first=P.M.|title=Prophecy and Discovery: On the Spiritual Origins of Christopher Columbus' 'Enterprise of the Indies|year=1985|publisher=[[American Historical Review]]|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Ian|title=Nostradamus: The Evidence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TqvuNAAACAAJ|date=2003|publisher=Orion Books Limited|isbn=978-0-7528-4279-0|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gerson, St\u00e9phane. ''Nostradamus: How an Obscure Renaissance Astrologer Became the Modern Prophet of Doom'' (New York: St. Martin's Press, 2012)  347pp\n* Mcmann, Lee. ''Nostradamus, The Man Who Saw Through Time'' (New York:Creative Page Express, Inc., 1941) at <span class=\"plainlinks\">[http://www.sacred-texts.com/nos/ ''Sacred Texts Archive'']</span> \n* Smoley, Richard, ''The Essential Nostradamus'' (Tarcher, Penguin, NY, 2006)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20191016072752/http://www.nostradamus.org/ Nostradamus.org]''\n* ''[http://www.secret-vault.co.uk/nostradamus/locations.html Secret Vault: Nostradamus Prophecy Locations]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Michel de Nostredame}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource author}}\n{{Wikisourcelang|fr}}\n* [https://www.holybooks.com/the-complete-works-of-nostradamus-pdf/ The Complete Works of Nostradamus] (Holybooks.com, PDF e-book)\n\n{{Nostradamus}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nostradamus| ]]\n[[Category:1503 births]]\n[[Category:1566 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century occultists]]\n[[Category:16th-century alchemists]]\n[[Category:16th-century apocalypticists]]\n[[Category:16th-century French physicians]]\n[[Category:16th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism from Judaism]]\n[[Category:Deaths from edema]]\n[[Category:Divination]]\n[[Category:French alchemists]]\n[[Category:French Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n[[Category:French occult writers]]\n[[Category:French people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]]\n[[Category:Prophets]]\n[[Category:Occitan people]]\n[[Category:University of Montpellier alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2601:c8:301:1bf0:7540:a8b3:784:dce6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nostradamus"}
{"title_page": "Dave Larson", "text_new": "{{Infobox Judge\n|name          = Dave Larson\n|image         = Dave Larson.jpg\n|imagesize     = \n|caption       = Dave Larson (born 1958) is an American lawyer and jurist from the U.S. State of Washington.\n|office        = Judge of the Federal Way, Washington Municipal Court\n|termstart     = 2008\n|termend       = \n|nominator     = \n|appointer     = \n|predecessor   = \n|successor     = \n|office2       = \n|termstart2    = \n|termend2      = \n|nominator2    = \n|appointer2    = \n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1958|01|01}}\n|birth_place    = [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]] \n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|spouse        = Debby\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Puget Sound]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n[[Seattle University School of Law]]\n}}\n'''Dave Larson''' (born 1958) is an [[Law of the United States|American lawyer]] and [[United States federal courts|jurist]] from the [[U.S. State]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. A nonpartisan office, Larson was appointed as City of Federal Way Municipal Judge in 2008, and was formally elected in 2009, and elected again in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theolympian.com/news/politics-government/article75234137.html|title=Federal Way Judge Dave Larson seeks Supreme Court seat|work=The Olympian|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis long career as a trial lawyer is best known for spearheading the landmark School Fair Funding Case,<ref name=\"Fair funding\">{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html|title=School district wins fair funding lawsuit|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=November 6, 2007|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> which was ultimately reversed by the Washington State Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/69894032.html|title=Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=November 12, 2009|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLarson is best known to the citizens of Washington State as one of the attorneys who helped stop the former owners of the Seahawks from moving the team from Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZEFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KI8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4106%2C1406765|title=Seahawk season-ticket holders sue|work=Ellensburg Daily Record|date=February 8, 1996|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nLarson was born in 1958 and was raised in [[Federal Way, Washington]],<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityoffederalway.com/page/judge-david-larson|title=Judge David A. Larson|publisher=City of Federal Way|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> where he attended Federal Way Public Schools.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>  He earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[Academic degree|degree]] from [[University of Puget Sound]] in 1980 and his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[Seattle University School of Law]] in 1984.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n\nIn 1986, Judge Larson began his own private practice. He spent the 23 next years as a [[trial lawyer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/381979551.html|title=Popular Federal Way judge running for state Supreme Court|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=June 6, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2000, Larson unsuccessfully ran for Justice for the Washington State Supreme Court. Larson is currently running for Justice for the Washington State Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/editorials/celebrate-competitive-state-supreme-court-races/|title=Celebrate competitive state Supreme Court races|work=The Seattle Times|date=May 26, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nLarson was appointed to fill a vacancy on the Metropolitan Court in 2008. He was formally elected to the same bench in 2009, and elected again in 2013.\n\n===''Federal Way School Board v. State of Washington''===\nIn 2006 the Federal Way School Board brought a lawsuit against the State of Washington to obtain greater income equity for teachers and staff.  The lawsuit was nicknamed the Fair Funding action.\n\nDave Larson was a member of the Federal Way school board during the lawsuit, and with his considerable experience as a trial attorney, Larson was the architect of the Fair Funding lawsuit.\n\nAbout the school board's motivation for the Fair Funding lawsuit, Dave Larson explained \"They're using a 1970s system to fund 21st century expectations.\"\n\nAt the time the lawsuit began against the State of Washington, Federal Way ranked 263 out of the 296 districts in dollars-per-student funding.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nFederal Way is the seventh-largest school district in the state. If the district had received the same amount as the highest-funded districts in the state, in the 2006-2007 school year, when the lawsuit was started, Federal Way could have received an additional $11.5 million in funding.<ref> \"Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit\". Federal Way Mirror. November 12, 2009</ref>\n\nJudge Heavey, presiding over the lower court, ruled in favor of the School Board.  Further, he found that \"the disparate funding violates the constitutional equal protection rights of Federal Way's teachers, students and taxpayers,\" Judge Heavey said in his published court opinion.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref> \n\nDave Larson opined \"It feels good that... (Judge Heavey) ruled the way he did. Justice was done today. It's really the end of an era for Federal Way schools,\" said Larson.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nFurther, Dave Larson predicted that the State of Washington would file an appeal with the Washington Supreme Court.   Larson mused that the Washington Supreme Court would likely grant the State a stay, and give the Legislature the opportunity to make immediate changes \"to do the right thing.  They can't ignore it\" Larson predicted.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nHowever, in November 2009 the Washington Supreme Court sided with the State and overturned the lower court's decision.<ref> \"Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit\". Federal Way Mirror. November 12, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Fair funding\"/>\n\n===''Seahawks Season Ticket Holders v. (The previous owners of the) Seahawks''=== \n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/feb/08/class-action-suit-targets-behring-season-ticket/|title=Class-Action Suit Targets Behring Season-Ticket Holders Join Kingdome Businesses In Suit|publisher=Spokesman.com|date=February 8, 1996|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLarson married his wife, Debby, in 1982. They have two boys: Andrew and Joshua.\n\n==Awards, positions, and honors==\n*2014 Sole Recipient of the Judge William Nevin Justice Award, awarded by former Chief Justice Gerry Alexander of the Washington Judge's Foundation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/community/278848901.html|title=Federal Way judge honored with prestigious award|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=October 14, 2014|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*Member of the Legislative Committee, Technology Committee, and Long-Range Planning Committee of the District and Municipal Court Judges Association (DMCJA)<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Past member of the Rules Committee and the Education Committee.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/> \n*DMCJA representative to the Washington State Bar Association Council on Public Legal Education and the DMCJA representative to the Data Management Steering Committee<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Instructor at the Washington State Judicial College<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*AV Peer Review Rating as a lawyer.  Per Martindale-Hubbell \"(An AV Peer Review Rating) is a testament to the fact that a lawyer's peers rank him...at the highest level of professional excellence.\"<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Member of the City of Federal Way Human Services Commission<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Chair of the City of Federal Way Board of Ethics from 1991-94.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former Member of the Federal Way School Board<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former commander of the Civil Air Patrol (Air Force Auxiliary) Squadron at McChord AFB<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Founder of the Aktion Club of Federal Way for disabled people<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former President of the Washington State Kiwanis<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former [[Scouting in Washington|Scout Leader]] and other positions in the [[Boy Scouts of America]]<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former Little League and Junior Football Coach<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960206&slug=2312784 County wants Seahawks suit venue change]\n*[http://www.bellinghamherald.com/news/state/washington/article82485027.html Bellingham Herald Newspaper]\n*[http://www.seattlepi.com/local/politics/article/Supreme-Court-challengers-appear-at-Republican-7780286.php The Seattle Post Intelligencer newspaper]\n*[https://ballotpedia.org/Dave_Larson ballotpedia.org]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Judge of the Metropolitan Court of the City of Federal Way|years=2008\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Larson, Dave}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2000 United States elections]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Puget Sound alumni]]\n[[Category:Seattle University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Federal Way, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Judge\n|name          = Dave Larson\n|image         = Dave Larson.jpg\n|imagesize     = \n|caption       = Dave Larson (born 1958) is an American lawyer and jurist from the U.S. State of Washington.\n|office        = Judge of the Federal Way, Washington Municipal Court\n|termstart     = 2008\n|termend       = \n|nominator     = \n|appointer     = [[X]]\n|predecessor   = [[Judge]]\n|successor     = \n|office2       = \n|termstart2    = \n|termend2      = \n|nominator2    = \n|appointer2    = \n|predecessor2  = \n|successor2    = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1958|01|01}}\n|birth_place    = [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]] \n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|spouse        = Debby\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Puget Sound]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n[[Seattle University School of Law]]\n}}\n'''Dave Larson''' (born 1958) is an [[Law of the United States|American lawyer]] and [[United States federal courts|jurist]] from the [[U.S. State]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. A nonpartisan office, Larson was appointed as City of Federal Way Municipal Judge in 2008, and was formally elected in 2009, and elected again in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theolympian.com/news/politics-government/article75234137.html|title=Federal Way Judge Dave Larson seeks Supreme Court seat|work=The Olympian|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis long career as a trial lawyer is best known for spearheading the landmark School Fair Funding Case,<ref name=\"Fair funding\">{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html|title=School district wins fair funding lawsuit|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=November 6, 2007|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> which was ultimately reversed by the Washington State Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/69894032.html|title=Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=November 12, 2009|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLarson is best known to the citizens of Washington State as one of the attorneys who helped stop the former owners of the Seahawks from moving the team from Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZEFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KI8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4106%2C1406765|title=Seahawk season-ticket holders sue|work=Ellensburg Daily Record|date=February 8, 1996|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and law career==\nLarson was born in 1958 and was raised in [[Federal Way, Washington]],<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityoffederalway.com/page/judge-david-larson|title=Judge David A. Larson|publisher=City of Federal Way|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref> where he attended Federal Way Public Schools.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>  He earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[Academic degree|degree]] from [[University of Puget Sound]] in 1980 and his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[Seattle University School of Law]] in 1984.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n\nIn 1986, Judge Larson began his own private practice. He spent the 23 next years as a [[trial lawyer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/381979551.html|title=Popular Federal Way judge running for state Supreme Court|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=June 6, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 2000, Larson unsuccessfully ran for Justice for the Washington State Supreme Court. Larson is currently running for Justice for the Washington State Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/opinion/editorials/celebrate-competitive-state-supreme-court-races/|title=Celebrate competitive state Supreme Court races|work=The Seattle Times|date=May 26, 2016|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nLarson was appointed to fill a vacancy on the Metropolitan Court in 2008. He was formally elected to the same bench in 2009, and elected again in 2013.\n\n===''Federal Way School Board v. State of Washington''===\nIn 2006 the Federal Way School Board brought a lawsuit against the State of Washington to obtain greater income equity for teachers and staff.  The lawsuit was nicknamed the Fair Funding action.\n\nDave Larson was a member of the Federal Way school board during the lawsuit, and with his considerable experience as a trial attorney, Larson was the architect of the Fair Funding lawsuit.\n\nAbout the school board's motivation for the Fair Funding lawsuit, Dave Larson explained \"They're using a 1970s system to fund 21st century expectations.\"\n\nAt the time the lawsuit began against the State of Washington, Federal Way ranked 263 out of the 296 districts in dollars-per-student funding.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nFederal Way is the seventh-largest school district in the state. If the district had received the same amount as the highest-funded districts in the state, in the 2006-2007 school year, when the lawsuit was started, Federal Way could have received an additional $11.5 million in funding.<ref> \"Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit\". Federal Way Mirror. November 12, 2009</ref>\n\nJudge Heavey, presiding over the lower court, ruled in favor of the School Board.  Further, he found that \"the disparate funding violates the constitutional equal protection rights of Federal Way's teachers, students and taxpayers,\" Judge Heavey said in his published court opinion.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref> \n\nDave Larson opined \"It feels good that... (Judge Heavey) ruled the way he did. Justice was done today. It's really the end of an era for Federal Way schools,\" said Larson.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nFurther, Dave Larson predicted that the State of Washington would file an appeal with the Washington Supreme Court.   Larson mused that the Washington Supreme Court would likely grant the State a stay, and give the Legislature the opportunity to make immediate changes \"to do the right thing.  They can't ignore it\" Larson predicted.<ref>http://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/18259989.html?mobile=true\nSchool district wins fair funding lawsuit\n</ref>\n\nHowever, in November 2009 the Washington Supreme Court sided with the State and overturned the lower court's decision.<ref> \"Federal Way School District loses fair funding lawsuit\". Federal Way Mirror. November 12, 2009</ref><ref name=\"Fair funding\"/>\n\n===''Seahawks Season Ticket Holders v. (The previous owners of the) Seahawks''=== \n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/feb/08/class-action-suit-targets-behring-season-ticket/|title=Class-Action Suit Targets Behring Season-Ticket Holders Join Kingdome Businesses In Suit|publisher=Spokesman.com|date=February 8, 1996|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLarson married his wife, Debby, in 1982. They have two boys: Andrew and Joshua.\n\n==Awards, positions, and honors==\n*2014 Sole Recipient of the Judge William Nevin Justice Award, awarded by former Chief Justice Gerry Alexander of the Washington Judge's Foundation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalwaymirror.com/community/278848901.html|title=Federal Way judge honored with prestigious award|work=Federal Way Mirror|date=October 14, 2014|accessdate=July 16, 2016}}</ref>\n*Member of the Legislative Committee, Technology Committee, and Long-Range Planning Committee of the District and Municipal Court Judges Association (DMCJA)<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Past member of the Rules Committee and the Education Committee.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/> \n*DMCJA representative to the Washington State Bar Association Council on Public Legal Education and the DMCJA representative to the Data Management Steering Committee<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Instructor at the Washington State Judicial College<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*AV Peer Review Rating as a lawyer.  Per Martindale-Hubbell \"(An AV Peer Review Rating) is a testament to the fact that a lawyer's peers rank him...at the highest level of professional excellence.\"<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Member of the City of Federal Way Human Services Commission<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Chair of the City of Federal Way Board of Ethics from 1991-94.<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former Member of the Federal Way School Board<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former commander of the Civil Air Patrol (Air Force Auxiliary) Squadron at McChord AFB<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Founder of the Aktion Club of Federal Way for disabled people<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former President of the Washington State Kiwanis<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former [[Scouting in Washington|Scout Leader]] and other positions in the [[Boy Scouts of America]]<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n*Former Little League and Junior Football Coach<ref name=\"Federal Way bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19960206&slug=2312784 County wants Seahawks suit venue change]\n*[http://www.bellinghamherald.com/news/state/washington/article82485027.html Bellingham Herald Newspaper]\n*[http://www.seattlepi.com/local/politics/article/Supreme-Court-challengers-appear-at-Republican-7780286.php The Seattle Post Intelligencer newspaper]\n*[https://ballotpedia.org/Dave_Larson ballotpedia.org]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Judge]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Judge of the Metropolitan Court of the City of Federal Way|years=2008\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Larson, Dave}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2000 United States elections]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Puget Sound alumni]]\n[[Category:Seattle University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Federal Way, Washington]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove unhelpful links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Larson"}
