{"title_page": "Edgar Buckingham", "text_new": "{{short description|American physicist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Edgar Buckingham\n| image = Edgar Buckingham by Pach Brothers c1886.jpg\n| caption = c1886\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1867|7|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1940|4|29|1867|7|8|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| field = Physics\n| work_institution = [[National Bureau of Standards]] \n| alma_mater = [[University of Leipzig]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Wilhelm Ostwald]]\n| doctoral_students = <!--please insert-->\n| known_for  = [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem]]\n| prizes = <!--please insert-->\n| religion = <!-- (Insert religious belief system/affiliation) used rarely by consensus-->\n}}\n'''Edgar Buckingham''' (July 8, 1867 in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] &ndash; April 29, 1940 in Washington DC) was an American physicist.\n\nHe graduated from [[Harvard University]] with a bachelor's degree in physics in 1887. He did additional graduate work at the [[University of Strasbourg]] and the [[Leipzig University|University of Leipzig]], where he studied under chemist [[Wilhelm Ostwald]]. Buckingham received a PhD from Leipzig University in 1893.  He worked  at the USDA Bureau of Soils from 1902 to 1906 as a soil physicist. He worked at the (US) National Bureau of Standards (now the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]], or NIST) 1906-1937. His fields of expertise included [[soil physics]], gas properties, [[acoustics]], [[fluid mechanics]], and [[blackbody radiation]].  He is also the originator of the [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem]] in the field of dimensional analysis.\n\nIn 1923, Buckingham published a report<ref>https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19930091225_1993091225.pdf</ref> which voiced skepticism that jet propulsion would be economically competitive with prop driven aircraft at low altitudes and at the speeds of that period.\n\nBuckingham's first work on [[soil physics]] is on soil aeration, particularly the loss of carbon dioxide from the soil and its subsequent replacement by oxygen. From his experiments he found that the rate of [[soil gas|gas diffusion in soil]] was not dependent significantly on the [[soil structure]], [[bulk density|compactness]] or [[water content]] of the soil. Using an empirical formula based on his data, Buckingham was able to give the diffusion coefficient as a function of air content. This relation is still commonly cited in many modern textbooks and used in modern research. The outcomes of his research on gas transport were to conclude that the exchange of gases in soil aeration takes place by diffusion and is ''sensibly independent of the variations of the outside barometric pressure''.\n\nBuckingham then worked on soil water, research for which he is now renowned. Buckingham's work on soil water is published in Bulletin 38 USDA Bureau of Soils: ''Studies on the movement of [[soil moisture]]'', which was released in 1907. This document contained three sections, the first of which looked at [[evaporation]] of water from below a layer of soil. He found that soils of various textures could strongly inhibit evaporation, particularly where capillary flow through the uppermost layers was prevented. The second section of ''Bulletin 38'' looked at the drying of soils under arid and humid conditions. Buckingham found evaporative losses were initially higher from the arid soil, then after three days the evaporation under arid conditions became less than under humid conditions, with the total loss ending up greater from the humid soil. Buckingham believed this occurred due to the self-mulching behaviour (he referred to it as the soil forming a natural mulch) exhibited by the soil under arid conditions.\n\nThe third section of ''Bulletin 38'' contains the work on unsaturated flow and [[capillary action]] for which Buckingham is famous. He firstly recognized the importance of the potential of the forces arising from interactions between soil and water. He called this the capillary potential, this is now known as the moisture or [[water potential]] (matric potential). He combined [[capillary]] theory and an energy potential in soil physics theory, and was the first to expound the dependence of soil hydraulic conductivity on capillary potential. This dependence later came to be known as relative permeability in petroleum engineering. He also applied a formula equivalent to [[Darcy's law]] to unsaturated flow.\n\n== Life and achievements ==\n {{Citation needed|reason=Most of these statements are made without reference and are not well-known facts.|date=February 2019}}\n* 1867 - Born in Philadelphia, PA on the 8th July\n* 1887 - Graduated from Harvard with a degree in physics\n* 1893 - Received a Ph.D. from the University of Leipzig\n* 1893 - Began teaching physical chemistry and physics at Bryn Mawr College\n* 1897-1899 - Wrote a textbook on thermodynamics<ref>{{cite journal|author=Hall, Edwin H.|authorlink=Edwin Hall|title=Review: ''Theory of Thermodynamics'', by Edgar Buckingham|journal=Bull. Amer. Math. Soc.|year=1902|volume=9|issue=3|pages=173\u2013175|url=http://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1902-09-03/S0002-9904-1902-00972-5/|doi=10.1090/s0002-9904-1902-00972-5|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* 1899 - Left Bryn Mawr and worked at a mining camp in Morenci, Arizona\n* 1901 - Married Elizabeth Holstein in Texas\n* 1901 - Started as an instructor in physics at the University of Wisconsin\n* 1902-1906 - Worked at the USDA Bureau of Soils, where he wrote and published 2 papers on the dynamics of gas and water in soils.\n* 1907 - Began working at the National Bureau of Standards (NBS)\n* 1918-1919 - Worked a stint as associate [[science attach\u00e9]] to the U.S. Embassy in Rome\n* 1923 - First NBS researcher to be given independent status, meaning he was freed of all administrative duties\n* 1937 - Retired from the NBS at the mandatory age of 70, however continued to work there on research problems\n* 1940 - Died in Washington DC on the 29th April\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060602062838/http://soil.scijournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/69/2/328 The Soil Physics Contributions of Edgar Buckingham] by John R. Nimmo and Edward R. Landa\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buckingham, Edgar}}\n[[Category:American soil scientists]]\n[[Category:American physicists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Strasbourg alumni]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison faculty]]\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American physicist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Edgar Buckingham\n| image = Edgar Buckingham by Pach Brothers c1886.jpg\n| caption = c1886\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1867|7|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1940|4|29|1867|7|8|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| field = Physics\n| work_institution = [[National Bureau of Standards]] \n| alma_mater = [[University of Leipzig]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Wilhelm Ostwald]]\n| doctoral_students = <!--please insert-->\n| known_for  = [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem]]\n| prizes = <!--please insert-->\n| religion = <!-- (Insert religious belief system/affiliation) used rarely by consensus-->\n}}\n'''Edgar Buckingham''' (July 8, 1867 in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] &ndash; April 29, 1940 in Washington DC) was an American physicist.\n\nHe graduated from Harvard with a bachelor's degree in physics in 1887. He did additional graduate work at the [[University of Strasbourg]] and the University of Leipzig, where he studied under chemist [[Wilhelm Ostwald]]. Buckingham received a PhD from Leipzig in 1893.  He worked  at the USDA Bureau of Soils from 1902 to 1906 as a soil physicist. He worked at the (US) National Bureau of Standards (now the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]], or NIST) 1906-1937. His fields of expertise included [[soil physics]], gas properties, [[acoustics]], [[fluid mechanics]], and [[blackbody radiation]].  He is also the originator of the [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem]] in the field of dimensional analysis.\n\nIn 1923, Buckingham published a report<ref>https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19930091225_1993091225.pdf</ref> which voiced skepticism that jet propulsion would be economically competitive with prop driven aircraft at low altitudes and at the speeds of that period.\n\nBuckingham's first work on [[soil physics]] is on soil aeration, particularly the loss of carbon dioxide from the soil and its subsequent replacement by oxygen. From his experiments he found that the rate of [[soil gas|gas diffusion in soil]] was not dependent significantly on the [[soil structure]], [[bulk density|compactness]] or [[water content]] of the soil. Using an empirical formula based on his data, Buckingham was able to give the diffusion coefficient as a function of air content. This relation is still commonly cited in many modern textbooks and used in modern research. The outcomes of his research on gas transport were to conclude that the exchange of gases in soil aeration takes place by diffusion and is ''sensibly independent of the variations of the outside barometric pressure''.\n\nBuckingham then worked on soil water, research for which he is now renowned. Buckingham's work on soil water is published in Bulletin 38 USDA Bureau of Soils: ''Studies on the movement of [[soil moisture]]'', which was released in 1907. This document contained three sections, the first of which looked at [[evaporation]] of water from below a layer of soil. He found that soils of various textures could strongly inhibit evaporation, particularly where capillary flow through the uppermost layers was prevented. The second section of ''Bulletin 38'' looked at the drying of soils under arid and humid conditions. Buckingham found evaporative losses were initially higher from the arid soil, then after three days the evaporation under arid conditions became less than under humid conditions, with the total loss ending up greater from the humid soil. Buckingham believed this occurred due to the self-mulching behaviour (he referred to it as the soil forming a natural mulch) exhibited by the soil under arid conditions.\n\nThe third section of ''Bulletin 38'' contains the work on unsaturated flow and [[capillary action]] for which Buckingham is famous. He firstly recognized the importance of the potential of the forces arising from interactions between soil and water. He called this the capillary potential, this is now known as the moisture or [[water potential]] (matric potential). He combined [[capillary]] theory and an energy potential in soil physics theory, and was the first to expound the dependence of soil hydraulic conductivity on capillary potential. This dependence later came to be known as relative permeability in petroleum engineering. He also applied a formula equivalent to [[Darcy's law]] to unsaturated flow.\n\n== Life and achievements ==\n {{Citation needed|reason=Most of these statements are made without reference and are not well-known facts.|date=February 2019}}\n* 1867 - Born in Philadelphia, PA on the 8th July\n* 1887 - Graduated from Harvard with a degree in physics\n* 1893 - Received a Ph.D. from the University of Leipzig\n* 1893 - Began teaching physical chemistry and physics at Bryn Mawr College\n* 1897-1899 - Wrote a textbook on thermodynamics<ref>{{cite journal|author=Hall, Edwin H.|authorlink=Edwin Hall|title=Review: ''Theory of Thermodynamics'', by Edgar Buckingham|journal=Bull. Amer. Math. Soc.|year=1902|volume=9|issue=3|pages=173\u2013175|url=http://www.ams.org/journals/bull/1902-09-03/S0002-9904-1902-00972-5/|doi=10.1090/s0002-9904-1902-00972-5|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* 1899 - Left Bryn Mawr and worked at a mining camp in Morenci, Arizona\n* 1901 - Married Elizabeth Holstein in Texas\n* 1901 - Started as an instructor in physics at the University of Wisconsin\n* 1902-1906 - Worked at the USDA Bureau of Soils, where he wrote and published 2 papers on the dynamics of gas and water in soils.\n* 1907 - Began working at the National Bureau of Standards (NBS)\n* 1918-1919 - Worked a stint as associate [[science attach\u00e9]] to the U.S. Embassy in Rome\n* 1923 - First NBS researcher to be given independent status, meaning he was freed of all administrative duties\n* 1937 - Retired from the NBS at the mandatory age of 70, however continued to work there on research problems\n* 1940 - Died in Washington DC on the 29th April\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060602062838/http://soil.scijournals.org/cgi/content/abstract/69/2/328 The Soil Physics Contributions of Edgar Buckingham] by John R. Nimmo and Edward R. Landa\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buckingham, Edgar}}\n[[Category:American soil scientists]]\n[[Category:American physicists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Strasbourg alumni]]\n[[Category:Leipzig University alumni]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison faculty]]\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "LiamTownsend", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added wiki hyperlinks.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgar_Buckingham"}
{"title_page": "Alt-right", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Loosely connected far-right, white nationalist movement based in the U.S.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Charlottesville 'Unite the Right' Rally (35780274914) crop.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Prominent alt-rightists were instrumental in organising the [[Unite the Right rally|\"Unite the Right\"]] rally in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], Virginia in August 2017. Here, rally participants carry [[Confederate battle flag]]s, [[Gadsden flag]]s and a [[Nazi flag]].]]\n[[File:Donald Trump alt-right supporter (32452974604).jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|An alt-right supporter at the [[March 4 Trump]] rally in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], Minnesota. (Image digitally altered<ref group=notes>The photograph has been altered to remove the copyrighted \"[[Pepe the Frog]]\" character which appeared in the lower left corner of the sign. Pepe the Frog is an [[Internet meme]] which has been appropriated by the alt-right as a symbol of the movement.</ref>).]]\n\nThe '''alt-right''', an abbreviation of '''alternative right''', is a loosely connected [[Far-right politics|far-right]], [[White nationalism|white nationalist]] movement based in the United States. A largely [[Internet activism|online phenomenon]], the alt-right originated in the U.S. during the 2010s, although it has since established a presence in various other countries. The term is ill-defined, having been used in different ways by various self-described \"alt-rightists\", media commentators, and academics. Groups which have been identified as alt-right also espouse [[white supremacism]], [[white separatism]], [[anti-immigration|severe immigration restrictions]], and [[antisemitism]].\n\nIn 2010, the American white nationalist [[Richard B. Spencer]] launched ''The Alternative Right'' [[webzine]]. Spencer's \"alternative right\" was influenced by earlier forms of American white nationalism, as well as [[paleoconservatism]], the [[Dark Enlightenment]], and the [[Nouvelle Droite]]. His term was shortened to \"alt-right\" and popularised by far-right participants of [[/pol/]], the politics board of web forum [[4chan]]. It came to be associated with other white nationalist websites and groups, including Andrew Anglin's ''[[Daily Stormer]]'', Brad Griffin's ''Occidental Dissent'', and Matthew Heimbach's [[Traditionalist Worker Party]]. Following the 2014 [[Gamergate controversy]], the alt-right made increasing use of [[trolling]] and [[online harassment]] to raise its profile. In 2015, it attracted broader attention\u2014particularly through coverage on [[Steve Bannon]]'s [[Breitbart News]]\u2014due to alt-right support for [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]]. On [[2016 United States presidential election|being elected]], Trump renounced the movement. Attempting to move from a web-based to a street-based movement, Spencer and other alt-rightists organised the 2017 [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], Virginia, which faced significant [[anti-fascism|anti-fascist]] opposition. After this, the movement began to decline.\n\nThe alt-right is a [[Scientific racism|biologically racist]] movement promoting a form of far-right [[identity politics]] for [[European Americans]]. Part of its membership supports [[Opposition to immigration|anti-immigrationist]] policies to ensure a continued white majority in the United States. Others call for the breakup of the country to form a [[white separatism|white separatist]] [[ethno-state]] in [[North America]]. Some alt-rightists seek to make white nationalism socially respectable in the U.S., while others\u2014known as the \"[[Fourteen Words|1488]]\" scene\u2014adopt openly [[white supremacism|white supremacist]] and [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] stances. Some alt-rightists are [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]], promoting a [[conspiracy theory]] that there is [[Zionist Occupation Government conspiracy theory|a Jewish plot]] to bring about [[White genocide conspiracy theory|white genocide]]; other alt-rightists view most Jews as members of the white race. The alt-right is [[anti-feminism|anti-feminist]], advocates for a more [[Patriarchy|patriarchal society]], and intersects with the [[men's rights movement]] and other sectors of the online [[manosphere]]. Alt-rightists generally support [[Anti-interventionism|anti-interventionist]] and [[Isolationism|isolationist]] [[Foreign policy|foreign policies]] alongside [[Protectionism|economic protectionism]]. Individuals aligned with many of the alt-right's ideas but not its white nationalism have been termed \"[[alt-lite]]\".\n\nThe alt-right distinguished itself from earlier forms of white nationalism through its largely online presence and its heavy use of irony and humor, particularly through the promotion of [[Internet memes]] like [[Pepe the Frog]]. Membership was overwhelmingly white and male, with academic and anti-fascist observers linking its growth to deteriorating living standards and prospects, anxieties about the place of white masculinity, and anger at increasingly visible [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] movements such as [[Black Lives Matter]]. Groups using the \"alt-right\" label have been characterised as [[hate group]]s,<ref name=\"ADL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/alt-right-a-primer-about-the-new-white-supremacy |title=Alt Right: A Primer about the New White Supremacy |website=Anti-Defamation League |accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/ideology/alt-right |title=Alt-Right |work=Southern Poverty Law Center|accessdate=December 27, 2017}}</ref> while alt-right material has contributed to the radicalization of white men responsible for various far-right murders and [[Right-wing terrorism|terrorist]] attacks in the U.S. since 2014.<ref name=\"SPLC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.splcenter.org/20180205/alt-right-killing-people|title=The Alt-Right is Killing People|work=Southern Poverty Law Center|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-report-white-supremacist-murders-more-than-doubled-in-2017/ |title=ADL Report: White Supremacist Murders More Than Doubled in 2017 |accessdate=January 26, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"DefenseOne\">{{cite news|accessdate=March 2, 2018|title=White Supremacists Killed More Americans Last Year Than Any Other Domestic-Extremist Group|url=http://www.defenseone.com/threats/2018/01/resurgent-threat-white-supremacist-violence/145243/|newspaper=Defense One}}</ref> Opposition to the alt-right has come from many areas of the political spectrum including [[Socialism in the United States|socialists]], [[Liberalism in the United States|liberals]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]]. Critics charge that the term \"Alt-right\" is merely a rebranding of white supremacism.<ref name=CQ>{{cite book|author=CQ Researcher|title=Issues in Race and Ethnicity: Selections from CQ Researcher|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cdE5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4|year=2017|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-5443-1635-2|pages=4\u20136|author-link=CQ Researcher}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology and scope ==\nThe term \"alt-right\" is a [[neologism]] first used in November 2008 by self-described [[Paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]] philosopher [[Paul Gottfried]], addressing the [[H. L. Mencken]] Club about what he called \"the alternative right\".<ref name=\"unz\"/> This talk was published in December 2008 under the title \"The Decline and Rise of the Alternative Right\"<ref name=\"Gottfried\">{{cite web |url=http://takimag.com/article/the_decline_and_rise_of_the_alternative_right/print |title=The Decline and Rise of the Alternative Right |first=Paul |last=Gottfried |website=Taki's Magazine|date=December 2008 }}</ref> in the [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] ''[[Taki's Magazine]]'', becoming the earliest published usage of the phrase in its current context according to [[Slate (magazine)|''Slate'']].<ref>{{cite web|first1=Osita|last1=Nwanevu|accessdate=2019-07-12|title=National Review Wants Credit for Opposing the Alt-Right Movement It Helped Create|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/03/how-national-review-helped-create-the-alt-right.html|date=23 March 2017|website=Slate Magazine}}</ref> Since 2016, the term has been commonly attributed to [[Richard B. Spencer]], president of the [[National Policy Institute]] and founder of ''Alternative Right''.<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Piggott |first1=Stephen |title=Is Breitbart.com Becoming the Media Arm of the 'Alt-Right'? |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2016/04/28/breitbartcom-becoming-media-arm-alt-right |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/alt-right-a-primer-about-the-new-white-supremacy |title=Alt Right: A Primer about the New White Supremacy |website=Anti-Defamation League |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170606170510/https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/alt-right-a-primer-about-the-new-white-supremacy |archive-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref> A white supremacist,<ref name=\"RichardSpencerWhiteSupremacist\">*{{cite news |last1=Peoples |first1=Steve |title=Energized white supremacists cheer Trump convention message |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/70541105d2f149cc9b7b6951d8a13e7a/energized-white-supremacists-cheer-trump-convention-message |work=Associated Press |date=July 24, 2016 |location=Cleveland, OH}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Wines |first1=Michael |last2=Saul |first2=Stephanie |title=White Supremacists Extend Their Reach Through Websites |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/us/white-supremacists-extend-their-reach-through-websites.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 5, 2015}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Gelin |first1=Martin |title=White Flight: America's white supremacists are ignored at home. So they are looking to start over with a little help from Europe's far right |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/foreigners/2014/11/jared_taylor_richard_spencer_and_american_white_supremacists_in_europe_why.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=November 13, 2014 |location=Budapest, Hungary}}\n* Chris Welch and Sara Ganim, [http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/06/politics/richard-spencer-interview-texas-am-speech/ White Supremacist Richard Spencer: 'We reached tens of millions of people' with video], CNN, December 6, 2016. \"Now Spencer, a 38-year-old white supremacist and founder of the so-called alt-right movement, is taking his rhetoric on the road{{nbsp}}...\"\n* Mangan, Katherine. \"A push to 'expand white privilege': Richard B. Spencer president, National Policy Institute, a white-supremacist group.\" The Chronicle of Higher Education, December 9, 2016, A6+.\n* Zalman, Jonathan. \"Neo-Nazi Website Tells Readers to 'Take Action' Against Jews on Behalf of Richard Spencer's Mother in Montana.\" Tablet Magazine, December 19, 2016. \"Critics of Richard Spencer the white supremacist, alt-right leader who dreams of an 'ethno-state' are making their voices heard{{nbsp}}...\"\n* \"Campus clashes as US white supremacist gives speech.\" ''London Evening Standard'' [London, England], December 7, 2016, p. 22. \"Hundreds of demonstrators clashed with riot police at a protest against a white supremacist's speech at a leading American university. Richard Spencer, who gained notoriety for holding a so-called 'alt-right' meeting celebrating Donald Trump's election triumph with Nazi rhetoric, told students attending the speech at the Texas A&M University last night: 'At the end of the day, America belongs to white men.'\"\n* Gretel Kauffman, [http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2016/1123/Donald-Trump-again-disavows-so-called-alt-right-supporters \"Donald Trump again disavows so-called alt-right supporters\"], ''Christian Science Monitor,'' November 23, 2016. \"Richard Spencer, coiner of the term \"alt-right\" and head of the white supremacist National Policy Institute{{nbsp}}...\"\n* Gretel Kauffman, [http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2016/1120/White-supremacists-convene-in-celebration-of-Trump-victory \"White supremacists convene in celebration of Trump victory\"], ''Christian Science Monitor,'' November 20, 2016. The annual conference of the National Policy Institute, a white supremacist think tank, experienced a rise in attendance this year... 'It's been an awakening,' Richard Spencer, president of the National Policy Institute, said at the conference.\"</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ehrenfreund |first1=Max |title=What the alt-right really wants, according to a professor writing a book about them |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/11/21/what-the-alt-right-really-wants-according-to-a-professor-writing-a-book-about-them |accessdate=November 24, 2016 |work=Washington Post |date=November 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Posner |first1=Sarah |title=Meet the Alt-Right 'Spokesman' Who's Thrilled With Trump's Rise |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/features/meet-the-alt-right-spokesman-thrilled-by-trumps-rise-w443902 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=October 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lombroso |first1=Daniel |last2=Appelbaum |first2=Yoni |title='Hail Trump!': White Nationalists Salute the President-Elect |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/11/richard-spencer-speech-npi/508379/ |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=November 21, 2016 |format=Includes excerpted video |accessdate=January 23, 2017}}</ref> Spencer coined the term in 2010 in reference to a movement centered on [[white nationalism]] and has been accused by some media publications of doing so to excuse overt [[racism]], [[white supremacism]] and [[neo-Nazism]].<ref name=\"ap\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Alternative Right |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/ideology/alternative-right |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |work=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wallace-Wells |first1=Benjamin |title=Is the Alt-Right for Real? |url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/benjamin-wallace-wells/is-the-alt-right-for-real |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=May 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldstein |first1=Joseph |title=Alt-Right Exults in Donald Trump's Election With a Salute: 'Heil Victory' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/alt-right-salutes-donald-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Definitions===\n\nThe term \"alt-right\" is sometimes ill-defined.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=3}}<ref>{{cite website |last=Caldwell |first=Christopher |date=December 2, 2016 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/02/opinion/sunday/what-the-alt-right-really-means.html |title=What the Alt-Right Really Means |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> This has been complicated by the various contradictory ways in which self-described \"alt-rightists\" have defined the movement and by the tendency among some of its political opponents to apply the term \"alt-right\" liberally to a broad range of right-wing groups and viewpoints.<ref name=\"Gray\"/> For instance, the conservative writer [[Ben Shapiro]] has stated that the [[American Left]] has attempted \"to lump in the Right with the alt-right by accepting a broader, false definition of the alt-right that could include traditional conservatism\".<ref>{{cite website |last=Shapiro |first=Ben |date=August 12, 2017 |title=Antifa & Alt-Right: Twin Cancers Eating America |website=[[National Review]] |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2017/08/antifa-alt-right-twin-cancers-eating-america/ |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box\n|quote=The 'alt-right' or 'alternative right' is a name currently embraced by some white supremacists and white nationalists to refer to themselves and their ideology, which emphasizes preserving and protecting the white race in the United States in addition to, or over, other traditional conservative positions such as limited government, low taxes and strict law-and-order. The movement has been described as a mix of racism, white nationalism and populism ... criticizes 'multiculturalism' and more rights for non-whites, women, Jews, Muslims, gays, immigrants and other minorities. Its members reject the American democratic ideal that all should have equality under the law regardless of creed, gender, ethnic origin or race.\n|source= \u2014The Associated Press<ref name=ap/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-37021991 |title=Trump's shock troops: Who are the 'alt-right'? |first=Mike |last=Wendling |website=BBC News |date=August 26, 2016 |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=left\n|width=30%\n|style=padding:8px;\n|bgcolor = #CCDDFF\n}}\n\nThe anti-fascist researcher Matthew N. Lyons defined the alt-right as \"a loosely organized far-right movement that shares a contempt for both liberal [[multiculturalism]] and mainstream conservatism; a belief that some people are inherently superior to others; a strong Internet presence and embrace of specific elements of online culture; and a self-presentation as being new, hip, and irreverent.\"{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=2}} The academic Tom Pollard referred to the alt-right as a \"socio/political movement\" comprising \"a loose amalgam of rightist groups and causes\" who \"shun egalitarianism, socialism, feminism, miscegenation, multiculturalism, free trade, globalization, and all forms of gun control\".{{sfn|Pollard|2018|p=7}} The journalist Mike Wendling termed it \"an incredibly loose set of ideologies held together by what they oppose: feminism, Islam, the Black Lives Matter movement, [[political correctness]], a fuzzy idea they call '[[globalism]],' and establishment politics of both the left and the right.\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=3}}\n\nThe [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] defined the alt-right as \"a set of far-right ideologies, groups and individuals whose core belief is that 'white identity' is under attack by multicultural forces using 'political correctness' and 'social justice' to undermine white people and 'their' civilization.\"<ref>{{cite article |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/ideology/alt-right |title=Alt-Right |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> The [[Anti-Defamation League]] states that \"alt-right\" is a \"vague term actually encompass[ing] a range of people on the extreme right who reject mainstream conservatism in favor of forms of conservatism that embrace implicit or explicit racism or white supremacy\".<ref>{{cite article |url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/alt-right-a-primer-about-the-new-white-supremacy |title=Alt Right: A Primer about the New White Supremacy |website=Anti-Defamation League |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe historian [[Timothy D. Snyder]] commented that {{\"'}}alt-right' is a term ... meant to provide a fresh label that would sound more attractive than 'Nazi,' 'neo-Nazi,' 'white supremacist,' or 'white nationalist.'\".<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Kurtis |title=President Trump says the 'alt-left' was partly to blame for the violence at Charlottesville. Wait: What's the alt-left? |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-alt-left-20170816-story.html |accessdate=August 17, 2017 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=August 6, 2017}}</ref> In 2016, the [[Associated Press]] (AP) described the \"alt-right\" label as \"currently embraced by some white supremacists and white nationalists\" that \"may exist primarily as a public-relations device to make its supporters' actual beliefs less clear and more acceptable to a broader audience\". The AP said that it has previously called such beliefs \"racist, neo-Nazi or white supremacist\".<ref name=ap/> Because the term was coined and used by white nationalists themselves rather than being applied to them by academic observers or by their opponents, the journalist Shaya Tayefe Mohajer urged their colleagues not to use the term \"alt-right\".<ref>{{cite article |last=Mohajer |first=Shaya Tayefe |date=August 14, 2017 |url=https://www.cjr.org/criticism/alt-right-trump-charlottesville.php |title=It Is Time to Stop Using the Term Alt-Right |website=[[Columbia Journalism Review]] |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> George Hawley, a [[political science|political scientist]] specialising in the U.S. [[Far-right politics|far-right]], disagreed with this approach, noting that using terms like \"white supremacist\" in place of \"alt-right\" conceals \"the ways the Alt-Right differs from other manifestations of the racial right.\"{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=3}} In 2017, the AP advised journalists to avoid using the term \"alt-right\", and that any usage should be surrounded with quotations or described as the \"so-called alt-right\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Montgomery |first1=Sarah Jasmine |title=Associated Press just laid down the law on why 'alt-right' is a bad term |url=https://www.dailydot.com/debug/associated-press-alt-right-antifa/ |website=The Daily Dot |accessdate=7 March 2020 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2016 description in the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', the alt-right is not formally organized and may not be an actual movement:<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/features/cpacs-flirtation-with-the-alt-right-is-turning-awkward-w468748 |title=CPAC's Flirtation With the Alt-Right Is Turning Awkward |last=Posner |first=Sarah |date=February 24, 2017 |work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> \"Because of the nebulous nature of anonymous online communities, nobody's entirely sure who the alt-righters are and what motivates them. It's also unclear which among them are true believers and which are smart-ass troublemakers trying to ruffle feathers\".<ref name=\"cjrCheckmate\"/> Many of its own proponents often claim they are joking or seeking to provoke an outraged response.<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> [[Andrew Marantz]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' describes it as \"a label, like '[[snob]]' or '[[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|hipster]],' that is often disavowed by people who exemplify it\".<ref name=\"NYer-Marantz\">{{cite journal |last1=Marantz |first1=Andrew |title=Trolls for Trump |journal=New Yorker |date=October 31, 2016 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/10/31/trolls-for-trump |accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Influences ===\nThe alt-right had various ideological forebears.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=21|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=6}} The idea of [[white supremacy]] had been dominant across U.S. political discourse throughout the 19th and early 20th centuries. After [[World War II]], it was increasingly repudiated and relegated to the [[far-right politics|far-right]] of the country's political spectrum.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=220}} Far-right groups retaining such ideas\u2014such as [[George Lincoln Rockwell]]'s [[American Nazi Party]] and [[William Luther Pierce]]'s [[National Alliance (United States)|National Alliance]]\u2014remained marginal.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=25}} By the 1990s, white supremacism was largely confined to neo-Nazi and [[Ku Klux Klan]] (KKK) groups, although its ideologues wanted to return it to the mainstream.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=220}} That decade, several white supremacists reformulated their ideas as [[white nationalism]], through which they presented themselves not as seeking to dominate non-white racial groups but rather as lobbying for the interests of [[European Americans]] in a similar way to how civil rights groups lobbied for the rights of [[African Americans]] and [[Hispanic Americans]].{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=220\u2013221}} Although white nationalists often officially distanced themselves from white supremacism, white supremacist sentiment remained prevalent in white nationalist writings.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=221}}\n\n[[File:2008 Jared Taylor.jpg|thumb|left|upright|The American white nationalist ideologue Jared Taylor became a revered figure among the alt-right, and the events organized by his [[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance group]] were attended by many alt-right members.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=27}}]]\n\nU.S. white nationalists believed that the United States had been created as a nation explicitly for white people of European descent and that it should remain that way.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=221\u2013222}} Many called for the formation of an explicitly [[White ethnostate|white ethno-state]].{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=221}} Various neo-Nazi and KKK groups adopted the term \"white nationalism\" and its associated rhetoric.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=225}} Seeking to distance themselves from such groups' violent, [[skinhead]] image, various white nationalist ideologues\u2014namely [[Jared Taylor]], [[Peter Brimelow]], and [[Kevin B. MacDonald]]\u2014sought to cultivate an image of respectability and intellectualism through which to promote their views.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=26\u201328|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=221}} Hawley later termed their ideology \"highbrow white nationalism\", and noted its particular influence on the alt-right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=26}} Taylor in particular became a revered figure in alt-right circles.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=27}}\n\nUnder the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[presidency of George W. Bush]] in the 2000s, the white nationalist movement focused largely on criticising [[mainstream]] conservatives rather than [[Liberalism in the United States|liberals]], accusing them of betraying white Americans.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=229}} In that period they drew increasingly on the [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] that had been generated by the [[Patriot movement]] since the 1990s; online, the white nationalist and Patriot movements increasingly conversed and merged.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=229}} Following the [[2008 United States presidential election|election]] of [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidate [[Barack Obama]] to the [[President of the United States|presidency]] in 2008\u2014making him the first black president of the country\u2014the world-views of a range of right-wing movements, including white supremacists, Patriots, conspiracy theorists, and [[Tea Party movement|Tea Partiers]], increasingly began to coalesce, in part due to a shared racial animus against Obama.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=231}}\n\nThe alt-right drew upon several older currents of right-wing thought. One was the [[Nouvelle Droite]], a far-right movement originating in 1960s [[France]].<ref name=\"WilsonGuardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/aug/23/alt-right-movement-white-identity-breitbart-donald-trump|title='A sense that white identity is under attack': making sense of the alt-right|last1=Wilson|first1=Jason|date=August 23, 2016|work=The Guardian|accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2016/08/25/the-disturbing-dawn-of-the-alt-right-donald-trumps-the-leader-of-a-dark-movement-in-america/ |title=The disturbing dawn of the alt-right: Donald Trump's the leader of a dark movement in America |website=Salon |date=August 25, 2016 |first=Heather Digby |last=Parton |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref> Many alt-rightists adopted the Nouvelle Droite's views on pursuing change through \"[[Metapolitics|metapolitical]]\" strategies;{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=13}} it thereby shares similarities with European [[identitarianism]], which also draws upon the Nouvelle Droite.{{sfn|Teitelbaum|2017|p=46}} The alt-right also exhibited similarities with the [[paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]] movement which emerged in the U.S. during the 1980s. Both opposed neoconservatism and expressed similar positions on restricting immigration and supporting an openly nationalistic foreign policy, although unlike the alt-right, the paleoconservatives were typically closely aligned to traditional Christianity and wanted to reform the conservative movement rather than destroy it.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=21, 29\u201332}}<ref>{{cite news |title=''National Review'' Fails to Kill Its Monster |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/128176/national-review-fails-kill-monster |website=The New Republic |last=Heer |first=Jeet |date=January 22, 2016 |accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/24/whats-the-alt-right-a-primer/ |title=What's the alt-right? A primer |first=David |last=Weigel |website=The Washington Post |date=August 24, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> Certain paleoconservatives, such as [[Samuel T. Francis]], moved far closer to the white nationalist position of the alt-right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=32\u201333}}\n\nThere were also links between the [[Libertarianism in the United States|American libertarian movement]] and the alt-right, despite libertarianism's general repudiation of identity politics.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=21, 33}} Many senior alt-rightists previously considered themselves libertarians,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=35}} and libertarian theorist [[Murray Rothbard]] has been cited as a particular link between the two movements due to his staunch anti-egalitarianism and support for ideas about differing IQ levels among racial groups.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=34}}<ref name=wapo2>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2016/09/02/where-did-donald-trump-get-his-racialized-rhetoric-from-libertarians/ |title=Where did Donald Trump get his racialized rhetoric? From libertarians. |first=Matthew |last=Sheffield |website=The Washington Post |date=September 2, 2016 |accessdate=August 28, 2018 }}</ref> Also cited in connection with the alt-right was the [[Dark Enlightenment]], or neo-[[reactionary]] movement, which emerged online in the 2000s, pursuing an anti-egalitarian message.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=46|2a1=Nagle|2y=2017|2pp=12\u201313}} This movement intersected with the alt-right;{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=12}} many individuals identified with both movements.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=46|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=12}} The Dark Enlightenment however remained distinct in not embracing white nationalism, deeming its focus on the entirety of the white race, as opposed to a small sub-set of individuals, too democratic.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=46|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=12|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=34}}\n\n=== Origins: 2008\u201313 ===\n[[File:Richard B. Spencer in 2016.jpg|thumb|upright|Richard B. Spencer claimed to have coined the term \"alternative right\" in 2008.]]\n\nAccording to Hawley, the alt-right began in 2008.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=50}} In November that year, the paleoconservative ideologue and academic [[Paul Gottfried]] gave a talk at his H. L. Mencken Club in [[Baltimore]]. Although the talk was titled \"The Decline and Rise of the Alternative Right\", it did not contain the phrase \"alternative right\" itself. Gottfried observed that, as the paleoconservative movement declined, a new cohort of young right-wingers were rising to take its place in challenging the neoconservative ideology then dominant in the Republican Party and broader U.S. conservative movement.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=51|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2pp=17\u201320}}<ref name=\"Gottfried\"/><ref name=\"Nwanevu\">{{cite article |title=Is the Term Alt-Right a Euphemism? |first=Osita |last=Nwanevu |website=Slate |date=August 31, 2016 |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/lexicon_valley/2016/08/31/the_history_of_the_alt_right_label_how_successful_has_it_been_in_shielding.html |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> One of those endorsing this idea was Richard B. Spencer, a fellow paleoconservative.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=237}} Born in 1978 to a wealthy family and raised in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]],{{sfn|Lachman|2018|p=80}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite article |title='Let's party like it's 1933': Inside the alt-right world of Richard Spencer |last=Cox |first=John Woodrow |date=November 22, 2016 |website=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/lets-party-like-its-1933-inside-the-disturbing-alt-right-world-of-richard-spencer/2016/11/22/cf81dc74-aff7-11e6-840f-e3ebab6bcdd3_story.html |accessdate=September 7, 2018}}</ref> in 2007 Spencer had dropped out of his PhD programme at [[Duke University]] to take up a position at ''[[The American Conservative]]'' magazine.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=53|2a1=Nagle|2y=2017|2p=52|3a1=Lachman|3y=2018|3p=81}}<ref>{{cite article |title=Richard Spencer rose as foremost voice in alt-right movement |website=ABC News |date=October 19, 2017 |url=https://abc13.com/politics/who-is-richard-spencer/2550923/ |accessdate=September 7, 2018 }}</ref> Spencer claimed he coined the term \"alternative right\" for the lecture's title, although Gottfried maintained that they were its joint creators.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=20}} As \"alternative right\" became associated increasingly with white nationalism in subsequent years, Gottfried distanced himself from it.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=52|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=19}}\n\nAfter ''The American Conservative'' fired Spencer, in 2008 he became managing director of [[Taki Theodoracopulos]]'s right-wing website ''[[Taki's Magazine]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=54|2a1=Lachman|2y=2018|2p=81}}<ref>{{cite article |title=I See a Darkness |last=Alm |first=David |website=The Point |url=https://thepointmag.com/2017/politics/i-see-a-darkness |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> The website initially contained contributions largely from paleoconservatives and libertarians, but under Spencer also gave space to white nationalists like Taylor.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=55}} In 2009, Spencer used the term \"alternative right\" in the title of an article by white nationalist [[Kevin DeAnna]];{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=236}} by 2010, Spencer had moved fully from paleoconservatism to white nationalism.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=237}} Spencer left ''Taki's Magazine'' and in March 2010 launched ''The Alternative Right'' [[webzine]].{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=56, 57|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=236|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=20|4a1=Lachman|4y=2018|4p=81}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Paleocon Starts New Extreme-Right Magazine |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |date=March 15, 2010 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2010/03/15/paleocon-starts-new-extreme-right-magazine}}</ref> Early issues featured articles by white nationalists like Taylor and MacDonald as well as the [[Heathenry (new religious movement)|Heathen]] [[Stephen McNallen]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=57}} Spencer noted that \"if you look at the initial articles for ''AlternativeRight.com'', that was the first stage of the Alt-Right really coming into its own\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=57}}\n\n''AlternativeRight.com'' consisted primarily of short essays,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=19}} covering a range of political and cultural issues.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=21}} Many of these reflected the influence of the French Nouvelle Droite, although this declined as the alt-right grew.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=36\u201337}} Spencer later stated that he wanted to create a movement distinct from the explicit [[white power]] image of neo-Nazi and KKK groups, noting that their approach to white nationalism was \"a total nonstarter. No one outside a hardcore coterie would identify with it\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=312}} In 2011 Spencer became the head of the white nationalist [[National Policy Institute]] and launched the ''[[Radix Journal]]'' to promote his views;{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1p=238|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=4}} in 2012, he stepped down from the ''AlternativeRight'' website and took it offline in December 2013.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=63, 64|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=4}} By that year, Spencer was expressing ambivalence about the \"alternative right\" label;{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=65}} he preferred to be called an \"identitarian\".<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Emergence: 2014\u201316 ===\n\nIt was on the Internet that Spencer's term \"alternative right\" was adopted and abbreviated to \"alt-right\";{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=236}} according to ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' magazine, the abbreviation \"retains the former phrase's associations\u2014the mix of alienation and optimism embedded in the act of proudly affirming an 'alternative' direction\u2014but compacts them into a snappier package.\"<ref name=\"Nwanevu\"/> The \"alt-right\" tag was created with public relations in mind, allowing white nationalists to soften their image and helping to draw in recruits from mainstream conservatism.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=243}} Many white nationalists gravitated to the term to escape the negative connotations of the term \"white nationalism\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=69}} Spencer thought that by this point, the \"Alt-Right\" had become \"the banner of [[white identity politics]]\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=68}}\n\nIt was on websites like [[4chan]] and [[Reddit]] that the term gained wider usage, and in 2015 began to grow in popularity.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=67}} Although there had previously been a strong [[Left-libertarianism|left-libertarian]] contingent to these online spaces, there was a gradual rightward turn in chan culture centred on 4chan's politics board, [[/pol/]].{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=13}} According to Hawley, the alt-right was \"an outgrowth of Internet troll culture\",{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=4}} and its emergence was marked by the online [[Gamergate controversy]] of 2014.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=47|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2pp=215, 233}}<ref>{{cite article |last=Lees |first=Matt |title=What Gamergate should have taught us about the 'alt-right' |website=The Guardian |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=September 12, 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/dec/01/gamergate-alt-right-hate-trump }}</ref> According to the journalist David Niewert, Gamergate \"heralded the rise of the alt-right and provided an early sketch of its primary features: an Internet presence beset by digital trolls, unbridled conspiracism, angry-white-male-identity victimization culture, and, ultimately, open racism, anti-Semitism, ethnic hatred, misogyny, and sexual and gender paranoia.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=215}} Gamergate politicized many young people, especially males, in opposition to the perceived [[culture war]] being waged by the cultural left.{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=24}} Through their shared opposition to political correctness, feminism, and multiculturalism, [[Imageboard|chan]] culture built a link to the alt-right.{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=16}} By 2015, the alt-right had gained significant momentum as an online movement.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=261}}\n\nNotable promoters of the alt-right included Spencer,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/richard-spencer-confronted-professor-over-alt-right-views-and-expelled-gym-613194 |title=Richard Spencer was expelled from a gym after a professor confronted him over his white nationalist views |last=Porter |first=Tom |date=May 22, 2017 |work=Newsweek|accessdate=May 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Vox Day]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/16/magazine/youtubes-monster-pewdiepie-and-his-populist-revolt.html |title=YouTube's Monster: PewDiePie and His Populist Revolt |last=Herrman |first=John |date=February 16, 2017 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 29, 2017 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Steve Sailer]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/04/steve-sailer-invented-identity-politics-for-the-alt-right.html |title=The Man Who Invented Identity Politics for the New Right |last=Willick |first=Park MacDougald, Jason |work=Daily Intelligencer|accessdate=May 29, 2017}}</ref> and Brittany Pettibone.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://observer.com/2017/01/gofundme-pizzagate-podcast-brittany-pettibone/ |last=Bonazzo |first=John |title=Alt-Right 'PizzaGate Expert' Starts GoFundMe for Her Podcast, Internet Revolts |date=January 30, 2017 |website=The Observer |accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref> Earlier white nationalist thinkers were also characterised as alt-right thinkers, among them Taylor,<ref name=\"tuttle\">{{cite website |last1=Tuttle |first1=Ian |title=The Racist Moral Rot at the Heart of the Alt-Right |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/433650/alt-rights-racism-moral-rot |work=National Review |date=April 5, 2016 |accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> and MacDonald.<ref name=ap/> Other prominent alt-rightists included Brad Griffin, a member of the [[Neo-Confederate]] [[League of the South]] who founded the ''Occidental Dissent'' blog,{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=238\u2013240}} Matthew Heimbach, who established the [[Traditionalist Worker Party|Traditionalist Youth Network]] in 2013,{{sfn|Michael|2019|p=73}} and [[Andrew Anglin]], who launched the ''[[Daily Stormer]]'' website\u2014named after the ''[[Der St\u00fcrmer]]'' newspaper active in [[Nazi Germany]]\u2014in 2013.{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1pp=248\u2013249|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=130}} By 2016, Anglin called the ''Daily Stormer'' \"the world's most visited alt-right website\".{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=249}} While some of the websites associated with the alt-right\u2014like ''The Daily Stormer'' and the Traditionalist Youth Network\u2014adopted neo-Nazi approaches, others, such as ''Occidental Dissent'', ''[[The Unz Review]]'', ''Vox Popoli'', and ''Chateau Heartiste'', adopted a less extreme form of white nationalism.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=4}}\n\n==== Breitbart News ====\nMany press sources described [[Breitbart News]] as an alt-right website.<ref>{{cite news |first=Eli |last=Stokols |title=Trump fires up the alt-right |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/donald-trump-full-breitbart-229767 |newspaper=Politico |date=October 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine  |title=The Rise of the alt-right |url=http://theweek.com/articles/651929/rise-altright |date=October 1, 2016 |website=The Week |accessdate=April 12, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Will |last=Rahn |title=Steve Bannon and the Alt-Right: A Primer |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/steve-bannon-and-the-alt-right-a-primer/ |website=CBS News |date=August 19, 2016  |accessdate=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The journalist Mike Wendling termed it \"the chief popular media amplifier of alt-right ideas\";{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=2}} Spencer described ''Breitbart'' as \"a 'gateway' to Alt Right ideas and writers\".{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=17}} Breitbart had been launched by the conservative [[Andrew Breitbart]] in 2005, but after his death in 2012 came under the control of [[Steve Bannon]], who took its coverage in a more aggressively right-wing direction.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=105\u2013107}} Bannon was a right-wing nationalist and populist;{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=129}} he was hostile to mainstream conservatism and referred to two prominent conservative publications, the ''[[National Review]]'' and ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', as \"left-wing magazines\" which he wanted to destroy.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=127}} Although much of its coverage fed into racially charged white narratives, Breitbart did not promote white nationalism;{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=129|3a1=Niewert|3y=2017|3p=246}} its differences from the mainstream conservative press were more in tone than in content.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=129}} In July 2016, Bannon told a journalist from ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' that Breitbart had become \"the platform for the alt-right\";<ref>{{cite article |last=Posner |first=Sarah |title=How Donald Trump's New Campaign Chief Created an Online Haven for White Nationalists |website=Mother Jones |date=August 22, 2016 |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/08/stephen-bannon-donald-trump-alt-right-breitbart-news/ |accessdate=September 7, 2018}}</ref>{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=129|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=17|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=105}} he may have been referring not to the website's official content but to its comments section\u2014which is lightly moderated and contains more extreme views than those put forward by Breitbart itself.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=109}} Hawley noted that whatever Bannon's motives for making this statement, it was untrue because Breitbart did not embrace the alt-right's underlying white nationalism.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=129}}\n\n{{Multiple image\n| align = left\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = Steve Bannon by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| image2 = Milo Yiannopoulos @NEXTConf 2014 (13925731458) (cropped).jpg\n| alt2 = \n| footer = Breitbart News amplified and popularised alt-right ideas under the editorship of \"alt-lite\" figure Steve Bannon (left); its articles by Milo Yiannopoulos (right) were particularly influential.\n| direction = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nIn March 2016, Breitbart writers Allum Bokhari and [[Milo Yiannopoulos]] published \"An Establishment Conservative's Guide to the Alt-Right\".{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1p=247|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=16|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=118}} In that article, they described the alt-right as being derived from the U.S. [[Old Right (United States)|Old Right]] and paleoconservatism, as well as the Nouvelle Droite and older right-wingers like [[Oswald Spengler]], [[Henry Louis Mencken]], and [[Julius Evola]]. Bokhari and Yiannopoulos' piece became \"perhaps the most widely cited article about the movement\" in the mainstream press;{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=118}} [[CNN]] described it as being similar to a [[manifesto]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/08/25/politics/alt-right-explained-hillary-clinton-donald-trump/ |title=Clinton is attacking the 'Alt-Right'\u2014What is it? |last=Krieg |first=Gregory |website=CNN |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=September 3, 2018}}</ref> Wendling characterized the article as a work of [[apologetics]] for the alt-right, noting that it downplayed the movement's more extreme elements and championed its counter-cultural value.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=119}} Hawley described the article as \"the most sympathetic portrayal of the movement to appear in a major media venue to date\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=145}} The commentator [[Angela Nagle]] suggested that Yiannopoulos did \"more than anyone else to give the alt-right a presentable face\".{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=49}}\n\nMany alt-rightists responded negatively to Bokhari and Yiannopoulos' article. ''The Daily Stormer'' referred to it as \"the Product of a Degenerate Homosexual and an Ethnic Mongrel\", with Anglin producing a response article titled \"A Normie's Guide to the Alt-Right\" in which he placed the 1488 scene at the centre of the movement.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=129}} On ''Occidental Dissent'', Griffin asked: \"What the hell does Milo Yiannopoulos\u2014a Jewish homosexual who boasts about carrying on interracial relationships with black men\u2014have to do with us?\"{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=16}} Various press sources termed Yiannopoulos \"alt-right\";<ref>{{cite web |title=Milo Yiannopoulos: Who is the alt-right writer and provocateur? |website=BBC News |date=February 21, 2017 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-39026870 |accessdate=September 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/who-is-milo-yiannopoulos-everything-you-need-to-know-about-donald-trumps-altright-poster-boy-a3404921.html |first=Phoebe |last=Luckhurst |date=November 25, 2016 |website=The Evening Standard |title=Who is Milo Yiannopoulos? Everything you need to know about Donald Trump's alt-Right poster boy |accessdate=September 7, 2018}}</ref> although Hawley noted that Yiannopoulos was \"not really part of the Alt-Right\" himself.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=48}} Observers have instead labelled Yiannopoulos \"alt-light\" or \"alt-lite\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=144|2a1=Nagle|2y=2017|2p=7}} The term \"alt-lite\" appeared in the alt-right's language in mid-2016, at which point it was used pejoratively for rightists who expressed some sympathetic views of the alt-right but did not share its white nationalism.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=143}} As well as Yiannopoulos, other prominent figures associated with the alt-lite included [[Mike Cernovich]] and [[Gavin McInnes]].{{sfn|Nagle|2017|pp=18\u201319}}\n\nOn September 9, 2016, several figures of the alt-right community held a press conference, described by one reporter as the \"coming-out party\" of the little-known movement, to explain their goals.<ref name=\"Weigel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/09/10/four-lessons-from-the-alt-rights-d-c-coming-out-party/ |title=Four lessons from the alt-right's D.C. coming-out party |last=Weigel |first=David |date=September 10, 2016 |work=Washington Post |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> They proclaimed [[Racialism (racial categorization)|racialist]] beliefs by stating: \"Race is real, race matters, and race is the foundation of identity\".<ref name=\"Levy\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/09/alt-right-makes-its-main-stream-debut |title=Alt-Right Movement Presents Its Vision for an All-White Society With Trump Paving the Way |last=Levy |first=Pema |date=September 9, 2016 |work=Mother Jones |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Speakers called for a \"white homeland\" and expounded on racial differences in intelligence. They also confirmed their support of Trump by saying, \"This is what a leader looks like.\"<ref name = \"Levy\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/hillary-clinton-alt-right-donald-trump-speech-2016-8 |title=Hillary Clinton: 'A fringe element has effectively taken over the Republican Party' |first=Maxwell |last=Tani |accessdate=August 25, 2016 |date=August 25, 2016 |work=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2016/08/why_hillary_clinton_is_talking_about_donald_trump_and_the_alt_right.html |title=How the \"Hipster Nazis\" of the Alt Right Got Big Enough for Hillary Clinton to Denounce Them |first=Michelle |last=Goldberg |accessdate=August 25, 2016 |date=August 25, 2016 |work=Slate}}</ref>\n\n=== Donald Trump presidential campaign: 2016 ===\n[[File:Donald Trump Laconia Rally, Laconia, NH 4 by Michael Vadon July 16 2015 19.jpg|thumb|right|The alt-right largely rallied behind the presidential candidacy of Donald Trump, although he distanced himself from the movement.]]\n\nIn June 2015, New York billionaire businessman [[Donald Trump]] announced plans to campaign to become the Republican nominee for the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], something that attracted the interest of alt-rightists as well as from white nationalists more broadly, neo-Nazis, KKK groups, and the Patriot movement.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=268}}\n\nThe alt-right was exceedingly vocal in support for [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/alt-hashtag-spurs-racism-rebukes-speech-41659771 |title='Alt-Right' Hashtag Spurs Racism, Rebukes During Speech |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/trailguide/la-na-trailguide-updates-neo-nazi-alt-right-crowd-cheers-the-1479774847-htmlstory.html |title=Neo-Nazi 'alt-right' crowd cheers the president-elect with 'Hail Trump' |last=Roy |first=Jessica |date=November 21, 2016 |work=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/features/meet-the-alt-right-spokesman-thrilled-by-trumps-rise-w443902 |title=Meet the Alt-Right 'Spokesman' Who's Thrilled With Trump's Rise |accessdate=October 20, 2016 |magazine=RollingStone |first=Sarah |last=Posner |date=October 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/the-alt-right-used-to-be-ignored-now-theyre-courting-a-president-elect/2016/11/10/746341d8-a75b-11e6-8fc0-7be8f848c492_story.html |title=The alt-right supported Trump. Now its members want him to satisfy their demands. |last=Sullivan |first=Kevin |date=November 10, 2016 |work=The Washington Post|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/199098/who-are-trumps-alt-right-supporters |title=Who Are Trump's Alt-Right Supporters? |last=Rosen |first=Armin |date=April 1, 2016 |work=Tablet|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> The alt-right approved of Trump's hard attitude to immigration, his [[Trump travel ban|calls for a ban on Muslims entering the U.S.]], and for [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|a wall to be built]] along the border with Mexico to curtail illegal immigration.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=198}} Niewert observed that \"Trump was the gateway drug for the alt-right\", with many individuals learning of the movement through their interest in Trump.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=292}}\n\nAs noted by Hawley, \"the Alt-Right is most definitely far to Trump's right\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=116}} Many alt-rightists recognized that Trump did not share their white nationalist world-view and would not bring about all the changes they desired.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=118\u2013119|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=14}} They were nevertheless grateful that he had shifted the national conversation rightward,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=118\u2013119}} and that he had shown that it was possible to successfully challenge the conservative movement from the right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=116}} Griffin called on alt-rightists to \"join the Trump campaign... to take down the hated [[cuckservative]] establishment\".{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=272}} A small minority of alt-rightists were against supporting Trump; ''The Right Stuff'' contributor \"[[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] [[Referee (association football)|Soccer Ref]]\" complained that two of Trump's children had married Jews, suggesting that Trump was therefore loyal to [[Israel]].{{sfn|Lyons|2017|pp=14\u201315}}\n\nTrump has been a keen user of [[Twitter]], and in November 2015 he retweeted a graphic about African-American crime statistics which included the alt-right, white nationalist hashtag \"#WhiteGenocide\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=121|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=278}}<ref>{{cite article |title=Trump's Pants on Fire tweet that blacks killed 81% of white homicide victims |date=November 23, 2015 |last=Greenberg |first=Jon |website=PolitiFact |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/nov/23/donald-trump/trump-tweet-blacks-white-homicide-victims/ |accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> The alt-righter [[RamZPaul]] rejoiced, retweeting Trump's piece with the comment: \"Trump watches and is influenced by the Alt Right\".{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=278}} Over coming months, Trump retweeted a second tweet that had \"#WhiteGenocide\" as a hashtag as well as sharing other tweets issued by white supremacists.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=279}}<ref>{{cite article |title=Donald Trump retweets 'White Genocide' Twitter user |first=Tal |last=Kopan |website=CNN |date=January 22, 2016 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/01/22/politics/donald-trump-retweet-white-genocide/ |accessdate=10 September 2018}}</ref> The alt-right saw this as further evidence that Trump was their champion.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=279}}\n\nBreitbart's Bannon had been one of Trump's most enthusiastic backers, and in August,{{when}} Trump appointed him to lead his election campaign.{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1p=289|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=107}}<ref name=\"Posner2\" /><ref>{{cite article |title=Donald Trump Appoints Media Firebrand to Run Campaign |first1=Jonathan |last1=Martin |first2=Jim |last2=Rutenberg |first3=Maggie |last3=Haberman |website=The New York Times |date=August 17, 2016 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/18/us/politics/donald-trump-stephen-bannon-paul-manafort.html |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> That month, the Democratic Party's nominee for the presidency, [[Hillary Clinton]], criticized Bannon's appointment in a speech given in [[Reno, Nevada]].{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=121\u2013122|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=299|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=196}} She highlighted Bannon's claim that Breitbart was \"the platform for the alt-right\",<ref name=\"Posner2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/08/stephen-bannon-donald-trump-alt-right-breitbart-news|title=How Donald Trump's New Campaign Chief Created an Online Haven for White Nationalists|last=Posner|first=Sarah|date=August 22, 2016|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=November 13, 2016}}</ref> attacking the alt-right as \"racist ideas ... anti-Muslim, anti-immigrant, anti-women ideas\" and accusing Trump of taking the alt-right \"mainstream\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/08/26/491452721/the-history-of-the-alt-right |title=What You Need To Know About The Alt-Right Movement |website=NPR |date=August 26, 2016 |accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref> In her speech, she said that while half of Trump's supporters were decent individuals \"desperate for change\", the other half were \"what I call the basket of deplorables ... The racist, sexist, homophobic, xenophobic, Islamophobic\u2014you name it. ... He has lifted them up. He has given voice to their websites that used to only have eleven thousand people\u2014now eleven million. He tweets and retweets their offensive hateful mean-spirited rhetoric.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=300}} Clinton referred to the alt-right as \"an emerging racist ideology\" and warned that \"a fringe element has effectively taken over the Republican Party\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=122|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=299|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=197}}<ref>{{cite article |title=Hillary Clinton's alt-right speech, annotated |date=August 25, 2016 |website=The Washington Post |last1=Ohlheiser |first1=Abby |last2=Dewey |first2=Caitlin |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/08/25/hillary-clintons-alt-right-speech-annotated/ |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/26/us/politics/hillary-clinton-speech.html|title=Hillary Clinton Says 'Radical Fringe' Is Taking Over G.O.P. Under Donald Trump|last=Flegenheimer|first=Matt|date=August 25, 2016|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> After Clinton's speech, web traffic to alt-right websites rose and the mainstream media gave it increasing coverage;{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=125|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=198}} Spencer and other alt-rightists were pleased, believing Clinton's speech gave them greater publicity and helped legitimize them in the public eye.{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1p=299|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=197|3a1=Lachman|3y=2018|3pp=79\u201380}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/alt-right-reaction-hillary-clinton-attack-speech-2016-8|title=The alt-right movement was practically giddy that Hillary Clinton attacked them in a major speech|last=Harrington|first=Rebecca|date=August 26, 2016|work=Business Insider|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref> Many of Trump's supporters adopted the moniker of \"deplorables\" for themselves, and the term was widely used on memes that the alt-right promoted online.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=301}}\n\nAs the election loomed, Trump claimed that the Obama administration would [[Electoral fraud|rig the election]] to ensure a Democratic win;<ref>{{cite article |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Burns |first2=Alexander |title=Officials Fight Donald Trump's Claims of a Rigged Vote |website=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/17/us/politics/donald-trump-election-rigging.html |date=October 16, 2016 |accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> far-right websites widely promoted this notion and claimed they would resort to violence or civil war in the event of Clinton's victory.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=308}} When Trump won the election in November, the alt-right's response was generally triumphalist and self-congratulatory.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=126|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=320|3a1=Lyons|3y=2017|3p=16}} Many alt-rightists claimed responsibility for the result. Anglin stated: \"Make no mistake about it: we did this. If it were not for us, it wouldn't have been possible\"; Spencer tweeted that \"The Alt-Right has been declared the winner... We're the establishment now.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=321}}<ref>{{cite web |date=November 12, 2016 |title=White Nationalists of the World Congratulate President-elect Trump |website=The Jerusalem Post |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/White-Nationalists-of-the-world-congratulate-President-elect-Trump-472384 |accessdate=7 September 2018 }}</ref> Following his election, Trump announced that Bannon would be his chief strategist, a decision popular with the alt-right.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=127|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=325}}<ref>{{cite article |last=Buncombe |first=Andrew |title=Steve Bannon: White supremacists celebrate Donald Trump's appointment of far-right Breitbart boss |website=The Independent |date=November 14, 2016 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/steve-bannon-white-supremacists-celebrate-donald-trumps-appointment-of-far-right-breitbart-editor-a7416661.html |accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref> Alt-rightists were generally supportive of Trump's other appointments, such as his decision to make [[Jeff Sessions]] his attorney general.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=326\u2013237}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Alt-right leaders praise Sessions as attorney general pick |website=The Washington Post |date=November 19, 2016 |last=Weigel |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/11/19/alt-right-leaders-praise-sessions-as-attorney-general-pick/ |accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref> While aware that Trump would not pursue a white nationalist agenda, the alt-right hoped to pull him further to the right, taking hardline positions that made him look more moderate, and thus shifting the U.S. [[Overton window]] in their direction.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=16}}\n\n=== After Trump's election: 2016\u2013present ===\nWendling suggested that Trump's election signalled \"the beginning of the end\" for the alt-right.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=207}} Celebrating Trump's victory, Spencer held a November meeting in Washington D.C. in which he stated that he thought that he had \"a psychic connection, a deeper connection with Donald Trump, in a way we simply do not have with most Republicans.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=327\u2013328}} He ended the conference by declaring \"Hail Trump! Hail our people! Hail victory!\", to which various attendees responded with [[Nazi salute]]s and chanting. This attracted significant press attention. When questioned on the incident, Spencer stated that the salutes were given \"in a spirit of irony and exuberance\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1pp=133\u2013134|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=328|3a1=Lyons|3y=2017|3p=17|4a1=Wendling|4y=2018|4pp=13\u201314}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/white-nationalist |title=Nazi salutes 'done in a spirit of irony and exuberance', alt-right leader says |last=Barajas |first=Joshua |newspaper=PBS NewsHour |accessdate=November 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Joseph |last=Goldstein |date=November 20, 2016 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/alt-right-salutes-donald-trump.html |title=Alt-Right Exults in Donald Trump's Election With a Salute: 'Heil Victory' |newspaper=New York Times |accessdate=November 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Trump was asked about the alt-right in an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]''. He responded: \"I don't want to energize the group, and I disavow the group.\"{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=134|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=328}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38069469 |title=Trump disavows 'alt-right' supporters |date=November 22, 2016 |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |website=BBC News}}</ref> This rejection angered many alt-rightists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/nov/22/alt-right-supporters-donald-trump-backlash-disavow-reddit-4chan|title=Donald Trump's 'alt-right' supporters express dismay at disavowal|last1=Woolf|first1=Nicky|date=November 23, 2016|website=The Guardian|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref> In April 2017, many alt-rightists criticized Trump's order to launch the [[2017 Shayrat missile strike|Shayrat missile strike]] against Syrian military targets; like many of those who had supported him, they believed he was going back on his promise of a more non-interventionist foreign policy in the Middle East.<ref name=\"CNNLabott\">{{cite news |last1=Labott |first1=Elise |last2=Gaouette |first2=Nicole |title=After Syria strike, populist supporters abandon Trump at home and abroad |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/04/07/politics/donald-trump-syria-populist-support/index.html |date=April 8, 2017 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=April 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Anthony |first1=Charles |title=Trump supporters are not happy about missile strikes on Syria |url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/supporters-donald-trump-twitter-are-not-happy-about-syria-airstrikes-347730596 |accessdate=April 9, 2017 |publisher= |work=Middle East Eye |date=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's Far-Right Supporters Turn on Him Over Syria Strike |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/07/us/trump-far-alt-right-syria.html |last=Haag |first=Matthew |date=April 7, 2017 |publisher= |work=The New York Times |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trump's Disillusioned Supporters |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/04/trumps-disillusioned-supporters/522336/ |last=Gray |first=Rosie |date=April 7, 2017 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] has included several figures who are associated with the alt-right, such as Senior Advisor to the President [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], Special Assistant to the President [[Julia Hahn]], former National Security Advisor [[Michael Flynn]], former Deputy Assistant to the President for Strategic Communications [[Michael Anton]], former Deputy Assistant to the President [[Sebastian Gorka]], former speechwriter Darren Beattie and former [[White House Chief Strategist]] Steve Bannon.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Haaretz]]|title=Alt-right Ally and Christmas Campaigner: Who Is Stephen Miller, Trump's Jewish Policy Adviser?|url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-who-is-stephen-miller-trump-s-jewish-policy-adviser-1.5474411|date=December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|title=Matt Gaetz Hires Speechwriter Fired From White House Over White Nationalist Conference|date=April 19, 2019|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/matt-gaetz-hires-dr-darren-beattie-speechwriter-fired-from-white-house-over-white-nationalist-conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Flynn, General Chaos|work=[[The New Yorker]]|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/02/27/michael-flynn-general-chaos|date=February 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/sebastian-gorka-former-trump-aide-accused-ties-nazi-group-heads-israel-660501|title=Sebastian Gorka: Former Trump Aide Accused Of Ties to Nazi Group Heads to Israel|work=[[Newsweek]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/world/2017/03/alt-right-leninist|title=The alt-right Leninist|website=www.newstatesman.com|accessdate=May 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[International Business Times]]|title=The White House 'ghost': Breitbart hardliner Julia Hahn to haunt Donald Trump's administration|date=January 13, 2017|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/white-house-ghost-breitbart-hardliner-julia-hahn-haunt-donald-trumps-administration-1603533}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Charlie|last=Sykes|title=How The Right Lost Its Mind|publisher=Biteback Publishing|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Birth Of A Radical|work=[[The Intercept]]|date=May 7, 2017|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/05/07/white-fear-in-the-white-house-young-bannon-disciple-julia-hahn-is-a-case-study-in-extremism/}}</ref> After Trump's election, other Republican candidates for office, such as [[Roy Moore]], [[Corey Stewart (politician)|Corey Stewart]], [[Josh Mandel]], [[Joe Arpaio]] and [[Paul Nehlen]], ran with the support of the movement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://forward.com/news/391159/paul-nehlens-campaign-shows-how-alt-right-culture-is-mainstreaming/|title=Jew-Hating Politician's Campaign Shows Spread Of 'Alt-Right' Culture|work=The Forward|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Newsweek]]|title=ALT-RIGHT MOVEMENT DESPAIRS AFTER ROY MOORE'S LOSS, BLAMES 'CUCKSERVATIVES'|date=December 13, 2017|url=http://www.newsweek.com/alt-right-movement-despairs-after-moores-loss-blames-cuckservatives-746399}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/jan/9/chris-murphy-raises-money-arpaio-senate-bid/|work=[[Washington Times]]|date=January 9, 2018|title=Democratic Sen. Chris Murphy raises money off Arpaio Senate bid}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Washington Post]]|title=Do Corey Stewart's Confederate antics help Ed Gillespie or hurt the GOP brand?|date=May 6, 2017|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/do-corey-stewarts-confederate-antics-help-ed-gillespie-or-hurt-the-gop-brand/2017/05/06/9e1872fe-2c1d-11e7-be51-b3fc6ff7faee_story.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[CNN]]|title=Trump says both sides to blame amid Charlottesville backlash|date=August 16, 2017|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/08/15/politics/trump-charlottesville-delay/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Forward]]|title=Why Is This Jewish Politician First In Line For Money From 'Alt-Right' Conspiracy Theorists?|url=https://forward.com/news/384531/why-is-this-jewish-politician-first-in-line-for-money-from-alt-right-conspi/|date=October 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Twitter began closing alt-right accounts it regarded as engaging in abuse or harassment;{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=162\u2013163}} among those closed were the accounts of Spencer and his NPI.<ref>{{cite article |last=Guynn |first=Jessica |title=Twitter suspends alt-right accounts |date=November 17, 2016 |website=USA Today |accessdate=September 10, 2018 |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2016/11/15/twitter-suspends-alt-right-accounts/93943194/}}</ref> In February 2017, Reddit then closed down the \"r/altright\" subreddit after its participants were found to have breached its policy prohibiting [[doxing]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=165}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/reddit-bans-alt-right-subreddit/ |title=Reddit shuts down 'alt-right' subreddit |newspaper=CNET|accessdate=February 14, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/feb/02/reddit-bans-far-right-groups-altright-alternativeright |title=Reddit bans far-right groups altright and alternativeright |last=Hern |first=Alex |date=February 2, 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=February 14, 2017 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Facebook]] followed by shutting down Spencer's pages on its platform in April 2018.<ref>{{cite article |title=Facebook shuts down white supremacist Richard Spencer's pages |last=Oppenheim |first=Maya |date=April 17, 2018 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/facebook-richard-spencer-pages-shut-down-alt-right-a8305621.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref> In January 2017, Spencer launched a new website, ''[[Altright.com]]'', which combined the efforts of the [[Arktos]] publishing company and the [[Red Ice Creations|Red Ice]] video and radio network.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=173|2a1=Lachman|2y=2018|2p=83}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Spencer Launches 'Alt-Right' Website on Martin Luther King, Jr.'s Birthday |last=Viets |first=Sarah |date=January 17, 2017 |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/01/17/richard-spencer-launches-alt-right-website-martin-luther-king-jrs-birthday |accessdate=September 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== The Unite the Right Rally and its aftermath ====\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 230\n| image1 = Nazi Salute (36543229556).png\n| image2 = Punch 3 (35754368344).jpg\n| caption2 = A participant at the Unite the Right rally gave a Nazi salute and was subsequently assaulted by counter-protesters.\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\n\nIn August 2017, the [[Unite the Right rally]] took place in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], Virginia, bringing together alt-right activists with members of other white supremacist and far-right movements.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=309}} Many alt-rightists thought that the rally would mark a turning point in the transformation of their movement from an online phenomenon into a street-based one.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=309}} At altright.com, editor Vincent Law for instance predicted before the event took place that \"People will talk about Charlottesville as a turning point\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=309}}<ref>{{cite article |title=A Guide to Who's Coming to the Largest White Nationalist Rally in a Decade |last=Sunshine |first=Spencer |website=Political Research Associates |date=August 10, 2017 |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |url=http://www.politicalresearch.org/2017/08/10/a-guide-to-whos-coming-to-the-largest-white-nationalist-rally-in-a-decade/#sthash.Oj3ECAtX.dpbs }}</ref> However, the event and its aftermath proved demoralizing for many in the movement.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=310}} A right-wing protester [[Charlottesville car attack|rammed his car into counter-protesters]], killing one and injuring 19 others; this incident brought much negative publicity to the event and its participants.{{sfnm|1a1=Atkinson|1y=2018|1p=310|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=174}} Although Spencer condemned the killing, other alt-rightists celebrated it.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=223}} Trump claimed that there were \"some very fine people on both sides\" of the Charlottesville protests, stating that what he called the \"alt-left\" bore some responsibility for the violence. Spencer stated that he was \"really proud\" of the president for those comments.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=175}}\n\nAlt-rightists who attended the rally often found themselves facing personal and legal repercussions for their involvement, while Internet service providers and mainstream social media websites subsequently terminated many alt-right accounts and sites.{{sfnm|1a1=Atkinson|1y=2018|1p=310|2a1=Phillips|2a2=Yi|2y=2018|2p=227}} Prominent figures like Spencer became reticent about organizing public protests of this kind in future.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=310}} He experimented with the use of flash demonstrations, returning to Charlottesville with a much smaller group for an unannounced protest in October.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=312}} Unite the Right exacerbated tensions between the alt-lite and more extreme elements of the movement.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=152|2a1=Atkinson|2y=2018|2p=310}} Breitbart distanced itself from the alt-right and criticized other media outlets that described them in such a manner,{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=215}} as did Yiannopoulos, who insisted he had \"nothing in common\" with Spencer.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=214}}\n\n==== Influence ====\nAlthough the movement saw significant gains in 2015 and 2016, it began significantly declining in power and membership in 2017 and 2018. This has been due to multiple reasons, including the backlash of the Unite the Right rally, the fracturing of the movement, more effective banishment of hate speech and harassment from major [[Social media|social media sites]] and [[Anti-fascism|widespread opposition by the American population]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news |last=Hayden |first=Michael Edison |url=http://www.newsweek.com/alt-right-fractured-violent-headed-trump-second-year-785552 |title=The alt-right is fractured, more violent headed into Trump's second year |date=January 21, 2018 |work=Newsweek |accessdate=January 21, 2018 }}</ref> In 2018, Heidi Beirich of the Southern Poverty Law Center described it as \"imploding\" while Marilyn Mayo of the Anti-Defamation League stated that the alt-right was in \"a downward spiral, but it doesn't mean they're going to disappear\".<ref name=\"imploding\">{{cite article |last=McCoy |first=Terrence |title='Imploding': Financial troubles. Lawsuits. Trailer park brawls. Has the alt-right peaked? |date=April 20, 2018 |website=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/imploding-lawsuits-fundraising-troubles-trailer-park-brawls-has-the-alt-right-peaked/2018/04/20/0a2fb786-39a6-11e8-9c0a-85d477d9a226_story.html |accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref> That year, Heimbach was arrested for the battery of his wife and father-in-law, resulting in the dissolution of his Traditionalist Workers Party,<ref>{{cite article |title=When the big tent collapses: private Discord posts offer an honest look at a perpetually dishonest movement |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2018/04/02/when-big-tent-collapses-private-discord-posts-offer-honest-look-perpetually-dishonest |date=April 2, 2018 |accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"imploding\" /> while Anglin went into hiding to avoid a harassment lawsuit, and Spencer cancelled his speaking tour.<ref name=\"imploding\" />\n\nThere has been widespread concern that as the chance of a large-scale political movement dies out, that [[Lone wolf (terrorism)|lone-wolf terrorist attacks]] from members will become common.<ref name=\":9\" /> In 2017, [[List of terrorist incidents|terrorist attacks]] and violence affiliated with the alt-right and white supremacy were the leading cause of extremist violence in the United States.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/1182778/the-far-right-was-responsible-for-the-majority-of-extremist-killings-in-2017/|title=The far-right was responsible for the majority of extremist killings in 2017|last=Mohdin|first=Aamna|date=January 18, 2018|website=Quartz|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref> Several alt-right candidates ran as Republican candidates in the 2018 elections. The neo-Nazi and [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust denier]] [[Arthur J. Jones|Arthur Jones]] ran for an Illinois congressional seat, the white supremacist [[Paul Nehlen]] for the Wisconsin seat of [[Paul Ryan]], the Republican Speaker of the House,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/alarm-white-supremacist-candidates-180207165333394.html|title=Alarm over white supremacist candidates in US|last=Strickland|first=Patrick|date=February 9, 2018|website=Al Jazeera|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref> and the neo-Nazi [[Patrick Little (Senate candidate)|Patrick Little]] for the [[United States Senate election in California, 2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/05/holocaust-denier-running-congress-180505125632779.html|title=Another Holocaust denier is running for US Congress|last=Strickland|first=Patrick|date=May 11, 2018|website=Al Jazeera|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/patrick-little-neo-nazi-california/|title=Is a Neo-Nazi Running as a Republican for the U.S. Senate in California?|website=Snopes|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== During coronavirus crisis ====\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics}}\nOn April 23, 2020, a report by the Tech Transparency Project identified Facebook groups that focus on the idea of a near-future U.S. civil war. There were 125 Facebook groups that call this future war the \u201cboogaloo\"; nearly all of these groups are \"private,\" meaning that their content is members-only.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/help/286027304749263|title=What\u2019s the difference between a public and private Facebook group and how do I change it? {{!}} Facebook Help Center {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> Half of the members of these groups had joined during the previous month while the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|US was affected by coronavirus]]. Daniel E. Stevens, executive director of Campaign for Accountability, said that \u201cboogaloo proponents...are directly advocating for violent action and tactically planning how to defeat government entities.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/boogaloo-facebook-pages-coronavirus-militia-group-extremists_n_5ea3072bc5b6d376358eba98|title=Amid The Pandemic, U.S. Militia Groups Plot \u2018The Boogaloo,\u2019 AKA Civil War, On Facebook|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=2020-04-24|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Beliefs ==\nThe alt-right has been characterized as belonging on the [[far-right politics|far-right]] of the political spectrum.{{sfnm|1a1=Lyons|1y=2017|1p=2|2a1=Mudde|2y=2019|2pp=60\u201361|3a1=Nagle|3y=2017|3p=9}}<ref name=\"FarRight\"/> There is no unifying manifesto behind the alt-right and different people who describe themselves as \"alt-rightists\" express different beliefs about what it wants to achieve.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=11}} There are nevertheless recurring attitudes that exist within the movement.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=11}} The alt-right's views are profoundly [[Anti-egalitarianism|anti-egalitarian]],{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=4}} and it rejects many of the basic premises of the [[Age of Enlightenment]] and [[classical liberalism]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=92}} For this reason, Hawley thought that \"the Alt-Right seems like a poor fit for the United States, where both the left and right have roots in classical liberalism and the Enlightenment.\"{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=36}}\n\nThe key division within the alt-right is between those who embrace explicitly neo-Nazi and white supremacist stances, and those white nationalists who present a more moderate image.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=135}} Wendling suggested that this was \"a distinction lacking a hugely significant difference\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=124}}\nThe white supremacist and neo-Nazi alt-rightists are sometimes termed \"1488s\", a combination of the white supremacist [[fourteen words]] slogan with 88, a coded reference to \"HH\", or \"[[Heil Hitler]]\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=68|2a1=Atkinson|2y=2018|2p=312|3a1=Phillips|3a2=Yi|3y=2018|3p=222}} These neo-Nazi elements represent a minority within the alt-right.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=14|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=124|3a1=Phillips|3a2=Yi|3y=2018|3p=222}} Many on the less extreme end of the movement are critical of them, believing that they \"go too far\" or generate bad publicity for it.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=14|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=136|3a1=Phillips|3a2=Yi|3y=2018|3p=222}} Some of the latter mock the neo-Nazi and explicitly white supremacist elements as \"Stormfags\", a reference to the white supremacist website [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]].{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=222}}\n\nThe concept has further been associated with several groups such as [[American nationalism|American nationalists]], [[National-anarchism|national-anarchists]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://psmag.com/news/the-principles-of-the-alt-right-have-been-around-for-nearly-a-century|title=Welcome to the New Age of Anarcho-Fascism|work=Pacific Standard|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref> and [[Monarchism|neo-monarchists]].<ref name=\"reuters\"/><ref name=\"WilsonGuardian\"/><ref name=\"bostonglobe\"/><ref name=\"MensRights\">{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/12/mens-rights-activists-are-flocking-to-the-alt-right.html|title=Men's-Rights Activists Are Finding a New Home With the Alt-Right|date=December 14, 2016|work=New York Magazine|accessdate=April 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYer-Marantz\"/>\n\n=== White nationalism ===\nThe alt-right is a white nationalist movement and is fundamentally concerned with white identity.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=11|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=2|3a1=Nagle|3y=2017|3p=8}} Spencer described the alt-right as \"identity politics for white Americans and for Europeans around the world\";<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alt-right-richard-spencer-punched-anti-donald-trump-protest-meme-pepe-the-frog-inauguration-day-a7541461.html |title=Alt-right leader Richard Spencer worries getting punched will become 'meme to end all memes' |date=January 23, 2017 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=February 25, 2017 |author=Maya Oppenheim}}</ref> he and some other alt-rightists identify as \"identitarians\".{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=223}} Not all members of the alt-right, however, actively embrace the term \"white nationalist\" in reference to themselves.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=11}} Hawley commented that the alt-right is, \"at its core, a racist movement\";{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=3}} similarly, the historian David Atkinson stated that the alt-right was \"a racist movement steeped in white supremacist ideas\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=312}} Attitudes to non-white people vary within the alt-right, from those who desire tighter restrictions on non-white [[Immigration to the United States|immigration into the U.S.]] to those who call for a violent [[ethnic cleansing]] of the country.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=16}}\n\n[[File:Charlottesville \"Unite the Right\" Rally (35780262984).jpg|thumb|left|Protestors at the 2017 Unite the Right rally, which was promoted by the alt-right. One man carries the logo of [[Vanguard America]], and another has a [[t-shirt]] depicting German Nazi leader [[Adolf Hitler]].]]\n\nIn contrast to the majority of scholars, who regard race as a socio-cultural construct, the alt-right promotes [[scientific racism]], making the claim that racial differences represent distinct biological differences. For the alt-right, this view is referred to as \"race realism\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=311}} There is a recurring tendency among alt-rightists to rank these racial groups on a hierarchy according to perceived [[IQ]] levels: this hierarchy has [[Asian people|Asians]] and [[Ashkenazi]] Jews at the top, followed by non-Jewish whites, then Arabs, and finally black Africans.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=85}} Unlike earlier forms of racist thought, such as those of the [[Interwar period|interwar]] [[Fascism|fascists]], the alt-right emphasizes the idea of racial difference above that of racial superiority, leaving the latter either implicit or secondary in its discourse.{{sfn|Gray|2018|p=148}} Most alt-rightists reject the label of \"white supremacist\".{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=222}}\n\nHaving analysed alt-right posts online, the political scientists Joe Phillips and Joseph Yi noted that a pervasive underlying theme was the belief that white people were victims and that white Americans had been disadvantaged by government policies such as [[affirmative action]] for non-white groups, assistance to [[illegal immigration|illegal immigrants]], and the perceived denigration of \"white history\" like [[Christopher Columbus]] and the [[Confederate States of America]].{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=222}} Alt-right online discourse also expressed much anger at the idea of [[white privilege]], often promoted by the American Left, with members citing job insecurity, under employment or unemployment, and growing mortality rates among whites as evidence that they do not lead privileged lives.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=222}} Alt-rightists wish to see an end to measures they believe disadvantage white Americans, including affirmative action, toleration of illegal immigration, and the public removal of symbols of \"white history\", such as statues of Columbus.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|pp=224\u2013225}} Spencer stated that \"anti-white animus in society at large is palpable.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas J. |last=Main |title=What's the Alt-Right? |url=http://touch.latimes.com/#section/-1/article/p2p-88717755/ |website=Los Angeles Times |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany alt-right figures have expressed the desire to push white nationalist ideas into the [[Overton window]]: the range of ideas tolerated in public discourse.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=313}} The alt-right has served as a bridge between white nationalism and traditional conservatism and as a tool used by white nationalists to push their rhetoric into the mainstream.<ref name=\"Hartzell\">{{cite journal|first1=Stephanie L.|last1=Hartzell|title=Alt-White: Conceptualizing the \"Alt-Right\" as a Rhetorical Bridge between White Nationalism and Mainstream Public Discourse.|url=http://derby.openrepository.com/derby/handle/10545/622321|journal=Journal of Contemporary Rhetoric |volume=8 |issue=1/2|date=2018|pages=6\u201325}}</ref> For instance, prominent alt-right figures on Twitter have used hashtag activism focused on the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]], combined with more mainstream-oriented alt-right hashtags, to bring more radical white nationalist beliefs into the mainstream.<ref name=WhiteGenocide>{{cite journal|first1=Wilson, Andrew|last1=Fergus|title=#whitegenocide, the alt-right and conspiracy theory: How secrecy and suspicion contributed to the mainstreaming of hate.|url=http://derby.openrepository.com/derby/handle/10545/622321|journal=Secrecy & Society|date=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany leaders of the alt-right movement, including include Spencer, Anglin, [[Mike Cernovich]], [[John Derbyshire]] and [[Kyle Chapman]] are married to, or have been romantically involved with, women of Asian descent. Writing in ''The New York Times'', the journalist Audrea Lim quoted an alt-right commenter who stated that \"exclusively\" dating Asian women was akin to a \"white-nationalist rite of passage\". Lim speculated that the trend may arise from \"the intersection of two popular racial myths\", that Asian-Americans are a hard-working, high-achieving, and well-behaved \"model minority\", and that Asian women are subservient and hypersexualized.<ref>{{cite website |last=Lim |first=Audrea |date=January 6, 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/06/opinion/sunday/alt-right-asian-fetish.html |title=The Alt-Right's Asian Fetish |website=The New York Times |accessdate=March 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====White separatism and ethno-states====\nThe alt-right is typically [[white separatism|white separatist]], with its members desiring autonomy and self-determination in their own white communities.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=224}} Some envision breaking up the United States into multiple states, each inhabited by a different ethnic or racial group.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=224}}\nSpencer has stated that he is not clear how the white ethno-state in North America would be formed.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=15}} He stated that \"I don't know how we're going to get there, because the thing is, history will decide that for us... You have to wait for a revolutionary opportunity to present itself, and history will present that opportunity.\"{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=15}} He suggested that it could be achieved through \"peaceful ethnic cleansing\", with non-whites given financial incentives to leave.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=22}} He compared his white nationalist movement for an ethno-state with the early days of [[Zionism]], which began in the 19th century with calls for the formation of a Jewish ethno-state and resulted in the formation of Israel in the mid-20th century.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=15}}\n\nMany alt-rightists are similarly unclear as to how a white ethno-state would actually be formed, but are content instead to promote the idea, particularly to people who had not previously considered it.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=15\u201316}} The prominent alt-rightist Greg Johnson suggested that it would come about after white nationalists became the dominant force in U.S. politics. At that point, he argued, the government would deport all undocumented migrants from the country and then introduce measures to encourage all other non-whites to emigrate from the country.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=16}} Other alt-rightists are critical of the idea of breaking up the United States into ethno-states, arguing that this would mean breaking up the country that their Euro-American ancestors fought to build.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=224}} They instead argue for restrictive immigration policies to ensure that the U.S. continues to be a white-majority state.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=226}}\n\nRather than seeking independent white ethno-states, some alt-rightists promote a pan-white empire spanning Europe and North America.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=172}} Spencer noted that he did not want his proposed white ethno-state to be small, and that he wanted it to eventually form part of \"a global empire... something on a very large scale. And that is a homeland for all white people, whether you're German or Celtic or Slavic or English.\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=24\u201325}} He described this as \"one big [[Roman Empire]]\" and suggested that it should engage in imperial expansion into the [[Near East]], focusing on conquering [[Istanbul]]; in Spencer's words, Istanbul was \"such a profoundly symbolic city. Retaking it, that would be a statement to the world.\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=25}} He added that its present [[Turkish people|Turkish]] inhabitants would be made to leave, for they could go to \"the Middle East or something. Who cares?\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=25}}\n\n====Anti-Semitism====\n[[File:YOU WILL NOT REPLACE US (-Charlottesville -UniteTheRight).webm|thumb|right|upright=1.6|Footage of right-wing protesters at the Unite the Right rally chanting \"you will not replace us\".]]\n\nSome elements of the alt-right are [[anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]] but others are tolerant of Jews.{{sfnm|1a1=Barkun|1y=2017|1p=439|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=10}}<ref name=\"Gray\">{{cite article |last=Gray |first=Phillip W. |title=The Alt-Right: An Introduction (Part I) |website=Oxford Research Group |url=https://www.oxfordresearchgroup.org.uk/blog/the-alt-right-an-introduction-part-i |date=19 December 2018 |accessdate=19 March 2019 }}</ref> Many in the alt-right believe that there is a Jewish conspiracy within the United States to achieve \"[[white genocide conspiracy theory|white genocide]]\", the elimination of white people as a racial group and their replacement with non-whites.{{sfnm|1a1=Atkinson|1y=2018|1pp=310\u2013311|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=44}} They believe that [[Zionist Occupation Government conspiracy theory|a Jewish cabal controls the U.S. government, media, and universities]], and is pursuing its aim of white genocide by spreading anti-white tropes and encouraging African-American civil rights groups.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=310}} As evidence for this supposed white genocide, these far-right figures point to the depiction of inter-racial couples or mixed-race children on television and the publication of articles discouraging women from having children early in life.{{sfn|Kelly|2017|p=73}} They also cite apparent instances of white self-hatred, including [[Rachel Dolezal]], an American woman of European descent who identifies as black.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=42}}\n\nThis anti-Semitic conspiracy theory is not new to the alt-right, but has recurred among far-right groups in [[Western world|Western]] countries since the 19th century; it was the reason for the Holocaust and various anti-Semitic pogroms in European history.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=310}} Andrew Anglin, one of the most prominent alt-right ideologues and a member of its neo-Nazi wing, stated \"the core concept of the movement, upon which all else is based, is that Whites are undergoing an extermination, via mass immigration into White countries which was enabled by a corrosive liberal ideology of White self-hatred, and that the Jews are at the center of this agenda.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=250}} In response to a ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' article portraying the movement as \"offensiveness for the sake of offensiveness\", Anglin said \"No it isn't. The goal is to ethnically cleanse White nations of non-Whites and establish an authoritarian government. Many people also believe that the Jews should be exterminated\".{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=254}}<ref name=NesbitHankes>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-09-12/what-is-the-alt-right |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121112806/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2016-09-12/what-is-the-alt-right |title=What Is the Alt-Right? |last=Nesbit |first=Jeff |date=September 12, 2016 |publisher=[[U.S. News and World Report]] |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2016/08/25/whose-alt-right-it-anyway |title=Whose Alt-Right Is It Anyway? |last=Hankes |first=Keegan |date=August 25, 2016 |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref> Other alt-rightists, like Spencer, welcome the involvement of Jews within their movement.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=7}}\n\n=== Opposition to neoconservatism and political correctness ===\nThe alt-right sought to hasten the downfall of U.S. conservatism,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=7}} and conservatives were often the main target of alt-right wrath.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=91}}\nThe prominent alt-right ideologue Brad Griffin stated \"Alt Right is presenting itself as a sleek new challenger to mainstream conservatism and libertarianism... Alt Right was designed to appeal to a younger audience who reject the Left, but who don't fit in on the stuffy or banal Right either.\"{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=239}} The anarcho-capitalist advocate [[Jeffrey Tucker]] has said that the alt-right is opposed to [[libertarianism]] because the alt-right focuses on group identity and tribalism instead of individual liberty.<ref name=fee>{{cite web |last1=Tucker |first1=Jeffrey |title=Five Differences Between the Alt-Right and Libertarianism |url=https://fee.org/articles/five-differences-between-the-alt-right-and-libertarians/ |publisher=[[Foundation for Economic Education]]|accessdate=September 7, 2016 |date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> The alt-right places little emphasis on economic issues.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=17|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=10}} Unlike mainstream U.S. conservatives, alt-rightists do not tend to favour [[Laissez-faire|laissez-faire economics]], and most appear to support President Trump's [[economic protectionism|protectionist economic measures]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}}\n\nPhillips and Yi noted that alongside \"[[white identity politics]]\", the alt-right promotes \"a message of expressive transgression against left-wing orthodoxy ('political correctness')\".{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=225}} Nicole Hemmer stated on [[NPR]] that [[political correctness]] is seen by the alt-right as \"the greatest threat to their liberty\".<ref name=\"NPR\"/>\nAlt-rightists often employ the term \"[[Cultural Marxism]]\"\u2014originally coined in reference to a specific form of [[Marxism|Marxist]] thought but popularised among the U.S. right-wing in the 1990s\u2014in reference to a perceived leftist conspiracy to alter society. They apply the term \"Cultural Marxism\" to a broad range of left movements.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=81\u201382}}\n\n===Isolationism and anti-interventionism===\n\nThe alt-right has no specific platform on U.S. foreign policy,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}} although has been characterised as being non-interventionist,<ref name=\"Hemmer\"/> as well as isolationist.<ref name=\"Nwavenu\"/> Generally, it opposes established Republican Party views on foreign policy issues.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}} Alt-rightists typically opposed President Bush's [[War on Terror]] policies,{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}} and spoke against the [[2017 Shayrat missile strike]].<ref name=\"Hemmer\">{{cite web |last=Hemmer|first=Nicole|authorlink=Nicole Hemmer |date=April 15, 2017 |url=https://www.vox.com/the-big-idea/2017/4/14/15290394/intervention-isolation-trump-america-first-syria |title=After the Syria strikes, right-wing non-interventionists are back in the wilderness |website=Vox |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Nwavenu\">{{cite web |last=Nwanevu |first=Osita |date=April 7, 2017 |url=https://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/04/07/why_the_alt_right_hates_trump_s_syria_strike.html |title=Why the Alt-Right Hates Trump's Syria Strike |website=Slate |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> The alt-right has no interest in spreading democracy abroad and opposes the U.S.' close relationship with Israel.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}}\n\nThe alt-right often looks favorably on Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]], viewing him as a strong, nationalistic white leader who defends his country from both radical Islam and Western liberalism.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=17|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=202|3a1=Pollard|3y=2018|3p=83}} Spencer praised Putin's Russia as the \"most powerful white power in the world\",{{sfn|Lachman|2018|p=80}} while prominent alt-rightist Matthew Heimbach called Putin \"the leader of the free world.\"{{sfn|Michael|2019|p=74}} Although during the [[Cold War]], the U.S. right-wing often presented the [[Soviet Union]] as the main threat to the U.S., links between the U.S. far-right and Russia grew during the 2000s, when prominent far-right activists like [[David Duke]] visited the country; the latter described Russia as being \"key to White survival\".{{sfn|Michael|2019|pp=65, 72\u201373}} The far-right Russian political theorist [[Aleksandr Dugin]] is also viewed positively by the alt-right.{{sfnm|1a1=Gray|1y=2018|1p=143|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=202}} Dugin has written for Spencer's websites,{{sfn|Michael|2019|p=73}} and Spencer's estranged wife, the ethnically [[Georgians|Georgian]] Nina Kouprianova, has translated some of Dugin's work into English.{{sfnm|1a1=Wendling|1y=2018|1p=202|2a1=Lachman|2y=2018|2p=80|3a1=Michael|3y=2019|3p=73}} Many alt-rightists also regard Syrian president [[Bashar al-Assad]] as a heroic figure for standing up to rebel groups in the [[Syrian Civil War]].{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=17|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=213}} Heimbach has endorsed a Shi'ite axis between al-Assad's Syria, Iran, and [[Hezbollah]] in Lebanon, seeing them as allies in the global struggle against Zionism.{{sfn|Michael|2019|p=74}}\n\n=== Anti-feminism and sex-related issues===\nThe alt-right is [[anti-feminism|anti-feminist]] and favors a more patriarchal society.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=17|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=7|3a1=Pollard|3y=2018|3p=79}} This is a stance shared by its female supporters, who represent a minority within the movement.<ref name=\"AtlanticWomen\">{{cite news |first=Caroline |last=Kitchener |accessdate=August 29, 2018 |title=The Women Behind the 'Alt-Right' |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-women-behind-the-alt-right/537168/ |website=The Atlantic |date=18 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HarpersWomen\">{{cite news |url=https://harpers.org/archive/2017/09/the-rise-of-the-valkyries/ |title=The Rise of the Valkyries |work=Harper's Magazine |accessdate=July 11, 2018 |date=September 2017 |first=Seyward |last=Darby}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/women-joining-alt-right |title=Why are women joining the 'alt-right' |website=PBS |date=August 19, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2018 }}</ref> Unlike many U.S. conservatives, the alt-right does not argue its anti-feminist position from traditional Christian perspectives, but claims that it is rooted in what it calls \"sex realism\", arguing that as a result of their biological differences, men and women are suited to different tasks in society.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}} Lyons commented that the alt-right was [[misogyny|misogynistic]] and presented women as irrational and vindictive.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=8}} Prominent female alt-rightists have experienced harassment and abuse from within the movement.<ref name=\"HarpersWomen\" /><ref name=\"AtlanticWomen\" /> ''The Daily Stormer'', for instance, banned female contributors and called for reduced female involvement in the white nationalist movement, producing an angry response from various white nationalist women.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=8}}\n\n[[File:Trump-WomensMarch 2017-1060165 (32298826522).jpg|thumb|left|A placard criticising the alt-right displayed at the [[2017 Women's March]].]]\n\nThe alt-right intersects with the [[manosphere]], an online anti-feminist subculture.{{sfnm|1a1=Lyons|1y=2017|1p=8|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2pp=59, 63}} There is overlap between the alt-right and the Men's Rights Activist movement, a part of the manosphere which believes that men, rather than women, face more oppression in Western society.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=17}} It also adopts the Men's Rights movement view that [[feminism]] has undermined and emasculated men, and believes that men should aggressively reassert their masculinity so as not to become \"beta males\" or \"cucks\".{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=311}} There has been some clear influence between the two movements; prominent manosphere ideologue [[RooshV]] for instance attended an NPI conference and quoted anti-Semitic material from white nationalist sources in his articles.{{sfnm|1a1=Lyons|1y=2017|1p=9|2a1=Nagle|2y=2017|2p=89}} Some alt-right figures have distanced themselves from the manosphere and its proponents; Greg Johnson of ''Counter-Currents Publishing'' was of the view that \"the manosphere morally corrupts men\" because it does not promote \"the resurgence of traditional and biologically based sexual norms\" but rather encourages [[rape culture]].{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=9}}\n\nOn social issues like attitudes to [[homosexuality]] and [[abortion]], the alt-right is divided; in contrast to the great attention U.S. conservatives have given these issues, they have been of little interest to the alt-right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=17\u201318}} Hawley suggested that the alt-right was more broadly pro-choice than the conservative movement.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=103}} Many on the alt-right favored legal abortion for its eugenic purposes, highlighting that it was disproportionately used by African-American and Hispanic-American women.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=103}} Some on the alt-right consider homosexuality to be immoral and a threat to the survival of the white race,{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=10}} with alt-right trolls having employed [[homophobia|homophobic]] terminology like \"[[faggot (slang)|faggot]]\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Michelangelo |last=Signorile |title=Donald Trump's Hate-Fueled, Alt-Right Army Hates 'Faggots' Too |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/donald-trumps-hate-fueled-alt-right-army-hates-faggots-too_us_57e11904e4b04a1497b67558 |website=The Huffington Post |date=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=October 30, 2016}}</ref> Others adopt a more tolerant stance and have praised gay white nationalists.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|pp=9\u201310}} This reflects a broader trend among white nationalists to denigrate gay culture while being more tolerant of gay writers and musicians like James O'Meara and [[Douglas P.|Douglas Pearce]] whose views they sympathize with.{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=10}}\n\n===Religion===\nThe alt-right is broadly [[Secularity|secular]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=100}} Many of its members are [[atheism|atheists]],{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=7}} or highly skeptical of [[organized religion]].{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=44}} Some alt-rightists identify as Christians;{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=102}} ''The Right Stuff'', for instance, hosted an alt-right Christian podcast called \"The Godcast\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=104}} There are also individuals in the movement who do not believe in Christian teachings but identify as [[cultural Christian]]s, admiring the Christian heritage of Western society.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=7}} Others on the alt-right [[Opposition to Christianity|oppose Christianity entirely]], criticizing it for its Jewish roots, for being a universal religion that seeks to cross racial boundaries, and for encouraging what they see as a \"slave morality\" that they contrast with perceived ancient aristocratic values.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=100, 101}} Some elements pursue [[modern Paganism]].{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=7}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/amp/article/517785/ |title=Breaking Faith |website=The Atlantic |date=April 2017 |last=Beinart |first=Peter |accessdate=February 8, 2018}}</ref> Although it agrees with the Christian Right's conservative stance on issues like abortion and same-sex marriage, white evangelical leaders of the [[Southern Baptist Church]] have angered the alt-right by expressing support for refugees entering the U.S., calling for measures to help undocumented migrants gain legal status, and urging members not to display the Confederate Battle Flag.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=101\u2013102}} Despite this, alt-right hostility to Christianity has waned over time, with many alt-right commentators identifying as Christian while rejecting mainstream Christian politics and most mainstream Christian religious leaders, especially [[Pope Francis]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=103\u2013104}}\n\nSeveral press sources have linked the alt-right to [[Islamophobia]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/islamophobes-white-supremacists-and-gays-for-trump-the-alt-right-arrives-at-the-rnc/ |title=Islamophobes, White Supremacists, and Gays for Trump\u2013the Alt-Right Arrives at the RNC |work=The Nation |date=July 20, 2016 |accessdate=October 1, 2016 |first=Joan |last=Walsh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lynch |first1=Conor |title=With their Orlando response, Trump and the alt-right are playing directly into the hands of ISIS |url=http://www.salon.com/2016/06/14/with_their_orlando_response_trump_and_the_alt_right_are_playing_directly_into_the_hands_of_isis/ |work=Salon |date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and Wendling stated that alt-rightists view Islam as a fundamental threat to Western society.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=7}} Hawley expressed the view that \"ironically, people on the Alt-Right are less Islamophobic than many mainstream conservatives\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=42}} He observed that many U.S. conservatives criticized Muslim migration to the United States because they regarded Islam as a threat to liberty; the alt-right has made little use of this argument. For alt-rightists, migration from Islamic-majority countries is undesirable not because the migrants are Muslims, but because most of them are non-white; it is equally opposed to non-white migrants who are Christian or non-religious.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=40\u201342}}\n\n== Structure ==\n{{quote box\n|quote=Alt-right groups live, recruit and coordinate (and hence evolve) online. And from what we can already see, they do so pretty much exactly like the pro-[[ISIS]] groups evolve and coordinate, but [[Facebook]] has so far been less quick to shut them down.\n|source= &ndash; Neil Johnson, extremist researcher<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/a-physicist-who-models-isis-and-the-alt-right-20170823/ |title=A Physicist Who Models ISIS and the Alt-Right |work=Quanta|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=right\n|width=30%\n|style=padding:8px;\n|bgcolor = #CCDDFF\n}}\n\nAccording to Hawley, the alt-right was \"a disorganized mob that broadly shares a number of goals and beliefs\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=70}}\nThe alt-right is not an organized movement, and has no formal institutions or leading elite.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=11|2a1=Lyons|2y=2017|2p=2|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3p=5}} It is a predominantly online phenomenon,{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=18|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=3}} lacking print newspapers and little radio or television presence.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=18}} It had no think tanks that influenced government policy and could not command the open allegiance of any major politicians or mainstream pundits.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=18}} Unlike many counter-cultural movements, it lacked [[soft power]] in the form of original bands, songs, films, and other cultural artifacts, of which it produced very few.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=9}} According to Hawley, it was the movement's success in using the Internet that allowed it \"to punch above its weight in the political arena\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=19}}\n\nThe alt-right made use of a large number of blogs, podcasts, forums, and webzines in which it discussed far-right political and cultural ideas.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=19}}\nThe use of the Internet by the far-right was not pioneered by the alt-right; the white supremacist web forum [[Stormfront (website)|Stormfront]] had for instance been active since 1996.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}} Where the alt-right differed was in its members willingness to leave far-right websites and engage in [[trolling]] on other parts of the Internet, such as the comments sections of major news websites, [[YouTube]], and Twitter.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}}\nAccording to Hawley, it was the alt-right's use of trolling which put it \"into the national conversation\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=19}}\n\nThe movement's online structure had strengths in that it allowed members to say things anonymously online that they would not be willing to say on the street or in another public place.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=26}} The lack of any formal organisation also meant that nobody could be kicked out of the alt-right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=26}}\n\nAs the alt-right developed, a number of formal, real world events were held, particularly through the National Policy Institute.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}} Members of the alt-right have also attended events organised by an older far-right white nationalist group, [[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}}\nThese events have gained a more limited audience than the alt-right's online activities.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}} This may be because operating online allows members of the alt-right to operate anonymously, while to attend events they must often expose themselves to journalists and protesters, thus making it more likely that their views will become publicly known.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}}\nU.S. alt-rightists have also sought to build links with other far-right and white nationalist groups elsewhere in the world. Heimbach for instance has addressed meetings of the [[Golden Dawn (political party)|Golden Dawn]] in Greece and the [[National Democratic Party of Germany]].{{sfn|Michael|2019|p=74}} Various U.S.-based alt-rightists used social media to encourage support for the [[Alternative for Germany]] party in that country's [[2017 German federal election|2017 federal election]].{{sfn|Morstatter|Galstyan|Shao|Karunasekera|2018|p=621}}\n\n== Tactics ==\nAlt-rightists often make reference to [[freedom of speech]] when calling for their views to be heard in public discourse.{{sfn|Hofmann-Kuroda|2017|p=369}} A recurrent tactic of alt-rightists is to present themselves\u2014as white men\u2014as victims of oppression and prejudice; this subverts many leftist arguments about other social groupings being victims and is designed to infuriate leftist opponents.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=73}}\n\nThe alt-right also make heavy use of imagery drawn from popular culture for its own purposes.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|pp=256\u2013257}} For instance, the American singer [[Taylor Swift]] is often held up as an idealised example of \"Aryan\" beauty.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=257}} When describing their own conversion to the movement, alt-rightists refer to themselves as having been \"getting red pilled\", a reference to a scene in the 1999 film ''[[The Matrix]]'' in which Neo, the protagonist, chooses to discover the truth behind reality by consuming a red pill.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=83|2a1=Kelly|2y=2017|2p=74|3a1=Niewert|3y=2017|3p=257}} On alt-right blogs and message boards, members often discuss how they were \"red-pilled\" originally.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=83\u201384}} Alt-rightists have also adopted [[milk]] as a symbol of their views; various members have used the words \"Heil Milk\" in their online posts while Spencer included an [[emoji]] of a glass of milk on his Twitter profile along with the statement that he was \"very tolerant... lactose tolerant!\"{{sfn|St\u0103nescu|2018|p=104}} The [[animal studies]] scholar Vasile St\u0103nescu suggested that this notion drew upon the 19th century pseudoscientific idea that Northern Europeans had become biologically superior to many other human populations because they consumed high quantities of milk and meat products.{{sfn|St\u0103nescu|2018|pp=104\u2013105}}\n\n=== Use of humor and irony ===\n\nThe alt-right makes strong use of humor and irony in its rhetoric.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=20|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=256}} As noted by Nagle, the alt-right's use of humor renders it difficult to tell \"what political views were genuinely held and what were merely, as they used to say, for the lulz.\"{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=2}} The alt-right presented an image which was much less threatening than that of earlier white nationalist groups, and thus was able to attract people who would be willing to visit alt-right websites who would not have considered attending neo-Nazi or KKK events.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=25}} As noted by Hawley, \"whereas older white nationalists came across as bitter, reactionary, and antisocial, much of the Alt-Right comes across as youthful, light-hearted, and jovial\u2014even as it says the most abhorrent things about racial and religious minorities.\"{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=20}} Members of the alt-right sometimes made fun of the earnestness and seriousness of earlier white nationalists such as William Pierce.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=76}}\n\nAnother of the tactics employed online by alt-rightists is to parody their leftist opponents. One teenaged American alt-rightist for instance created a Twitter account for a fictional individual whom they described as an \"LGBTQ+ pansexual nonbinary POC transwoman\" who was a \"Journalist for BLM. Always stayin [[woke]]\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=49\u201350}} Alt-rightists also orchestrated pranks, again to cause alarm among opponents. For instance, during the 2016 presidential campaign alt-rightists presented claims that they were plotting to send representatives posing as officials to voting booths where they would suppress ethnic minority turnout. There was no such plot, but press sources like ''[[Politico]]'' picked up on the claims and presented them as fact.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=75\u201376}} Such incidents reflected the alt-right's willingness to lie to advance their interests.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=75}} This tendency toward trolling renders it difficult for journalists to learn more about the alt-right because those members they talked to were willing to deceive them for their amusement.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=74}}\n\nNagle suggested that the alt-right's use of such tactics made it strongly transgressive and thus part of a tradition that she traced back to the work of the [[Marquis de Sade]] in the 18th century.{{sfn|Nagle|2017|pp=28\u201329}} She argued that it was with the alt-right that \"the transgressive anti-moral style\" reached \"its final detachment from any egalitarian philosophy of the left or Christian morality of the right\".{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=39}}\n\n===Use of memes===\n[[File:Feels good man.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.7|The Pepe the Frog meme, originally created in 2005, was adopted by the alt-right and became a \"mascot\" for the movement.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=2|2a1=Lachman|2y=2018|2p=89}}]]\n\nThe alt-right also makes heavy use of [[Internet meme|memes]].{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=81|2a1=Pollard|2y=2018|2p=77}}<ref name=\"NYTechoes\">{{cite news |last=Hess |first=Amanda |title=For the Alt-Right, the Message Is in the Punctuation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/11/arts/for-the-alt-right-the-message-is-in-the-punctuation.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=June 10, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/read/nero-nazis-and-the-new-far-right-the-phenomena-of-the-professional-troll |title=Nero, Nazis, and the New Far Right: The Phenomena of the Professional Troll |first=Jake |last=Kivan\u00e7 |date=June 15, 2016 |accessdate=July 14, 2016 |work=Vice}}</ref> The alt-right adopted much of its \"image- and humor-based culture\", including its heavy use of memes, from the online subcultures active at 4chan and later 8chan.{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=13}} These memes are then used to try and influence public opinion.{{sfn|Pollard|2018|p=77}} The prevalence of such memes in alt-right circles has led some commentators to question whether the alt-right is a serious movement rather than just an alternative way to express traditionally conservative beliefs,<ref name=\"NYTechoes\"/><ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> with Chava Gourarie of the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'' stating that provoking a media reaction to these memes is for some creators an end in itself.<ref name=\"cjrCheckmate\"/> The political scientist [[Marc Hetherington]] sees these memes as an effort to legitimize racist views.<ref name=\"csmonitor-jonsson\"/>\n\nOne of the most commonly used memes within the alt-right is [[Pepe the Frog]].{{sfnm|1a1=Niewert|1y=2017|1p=255|2a1=Pollard|2y=2018|2p=82}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/05/26/how-pepe-the-frog-became-a-nazi-trump-supporter-and-alt-right-symbol.html |title=How Pepe the Frog Became a Nazi Trump Supporter and Alt-Right Symbol |first=Olivia |last=Nuzzi |accessdate=September 17, 2016 |date=May 25, 2016 |work=The Daily Beast}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Suebsaeng |first1=Asawin |title=White Nationalists and Nazi-Saluting Tila Tequila Toast 'Emperor Trump' in Washington, DC |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/11/19/white-nationalists-and-nazi-saluting-tila-tequila-toast-emperor-trump-in-washington-dc.html |website=The Daily Beast |accessdate=November 22, 2016 |date=November 19, 2016}}</ref> The Pepe meme was created by artist [[Matt Furie]] in 2005 and over following years spread through the Internet, being shared by pop stars like [[Nicki Minaj]] and [[Katy Perry]].{{sfnm|1a1=Lachman|1y=2018|1p=85|2a1=Pollard|2y=2018|2p=82}} By 2014, Pepe was one of the most popular online memes, used among far-right trolls on 4chan and from there adopted by the alt-right.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=2|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=255}} After Trump tweeted a meme of Pepe as himself, and his son [[Donald Trump Jr]] posted a Pepe meme shortly after, alt-righters and 4channers began spreading the meme with political intent.{{sfn|Lachman|2018|p=89}} According to writer [[Gary Lachman]], Pepe became \"the unofficial mascot of the alt-right movement\".{{sfn|Lachman|2018|p=89}} The use of Pepe spawned the satirical worship of the Ancient Egyptian frog-headed deity [[Kek (mythology)|Kek]], as well as satirical nationalism of the nonexistent nation of \"Kekistan\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/05/08/what-kek-explaining-alt-right-deity-behind-their-meme-magic |title=What the Kek: Explaining the Alt-Right 'Deity' Behind Their 'Meme Magic' |last=Neiwert |first=David |date=May 8, 2017 |website=Southern Poverty Law Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519155921/https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/05/08/what-kek-explaining-alt-right-deity-behind-their-meme-magic|archive-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-37431509|title=Farage, the God Kek and modern politics|first=Mark|last=Mardell|date=September 22, 2016|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vocativ.com/377958/alt-right-richard-spencer/|title=Beyond Trump: The Alt-Right's Plan For Its All White Pipe-Dream|date=November 22, 2016|website=Vocativ}}</ref>\n\nAnother alt-right mascot was [[Moon Man (Internet meme)|Moon Man]], an unofficial parody of [[McDonald's]] 1980s Mac Tonight character.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=84}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/2016/10/25/meet-moon-man-the-alt-rights-new-racist-rap-sensation-borrowed-from-1980s-mcdonalds-ads/| title=Meet Moon Man: The alt-right's racist rap sensation borrowed from 1980s McDonald's ads |last= Sheffield |first= Matthew |date=October 25, 2016 |website=Salon |accessdate=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Trump-Inspired Pepe The Frog Billboards To Hit Battleground State|url=http://www.vocativ.com/365460/trump-pepe-billboards/|accessdate=November 26, 2016 |website=Vocativ|date=6 October 2016}}</ref> Alt-rightists posted videos to YouTube in which Moon Man rapped to songs they had composed like \"Black Lives Don't Matter\" by a text-to-speech synthesizer.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=84}}\n\nThe alt-right employed various memes for individuals outside the movement. White people who were not part of the movement were called \"normies\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=74|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2p=90}} An alt-right acronym was \"WEIRD\", for \"Western, educated, industrialised, rich and democratic people\".{{sfn|Salazar|2018|p=138}} Mainstream conservatives were often denigrated as \"cuckservatives\", a portmanteau of \"[[cuckold]]\" and \"conservative\".{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=94|2a1=Niewert|2y=2017|2p=257|3a1=Lyons|3y=2017|3p=15|4a1=Pollard|4y=2018|4p=79}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Weigel |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/07/29/cuckservative-the-conservative-insult-of-the-month-explained/ |title='Cuckservative' \u2013 the conservative insult of the month, explained |website=The Washington Post |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gq.com/story/why-angry-white-men-love-calling-people-cucks |title=Why Angry White Men Love Calling People \"Cucks\" |last=Schwartz |first=Dana |date=August 1, 2016 |website=GQ|archive-url=https://archive.is/20170610184804/http://www.gq.com/story/why-angry-white-men-love-calling-people-cucks |archive-date=June 10, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> The term \"cuckold\" pertains to a man with an unfaithful wife; the alt-right saw this as analogous to the role of the U.S. conservative movement in assisting non-whites in the U.S.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=94}}<ref group=\"notes\">The derivative term \"cuck\" also refers to a genre of pornography in which men watch their wives or girlfriends have sex with another man. Kelly 2017, pp. 74\u201375; Lyons 2017, p. 15.</ref>\n\nVarious terms were also used for leftists. Those who expressed [[Progressivism|progressive]] views, particularly online, were characterised as \"[[social justice warrior]]s\" (SJWs).{{sfnm|1a1=Wendling|1y=2018|1p=95|2a1=Salazar|2y=2018|2p=138}} Individuals who expressed leftist opinions on [[Tumblr]]\u2014and who alt-rightists often stereotyped as fat, ugly feminists\u2014were called \"Tumblrinas\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=97}} The term \"[[Snowflake (slang)|snowflake]]\", short for \"special snowflake\", was used as a pejorative for such individuals,<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Roy |url = http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-pol-alt-right-terminology-20161115-story.html |title = 'Cuck,' 'snowflake,' 'masculinist': A guide to the language of the 'alt-right' |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 16, 2016 |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> and in reference to leftist uses of \"[[trigger warnings]]\", alt-rightists expressed a desire to \"trigger\" leftists by upsetting them.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=97}} Leftists who professed victim status while harassing or bullying others were labelled \"crybullies\",{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=80}} while leftists who were perceived to be stupid were labelled \"libtards\", a neologism of \"liberal\" and \"retard\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=87}}\n\n[[File:Trump supporters May Day 2017 in New York City(34430306665) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|A young man displaying the flag of Kekistan at a pro-Trump rally; the flag is an alt-right symbol.]]\n\nWhen referring to African-Americans, alt-rightists regularly employed the meme \"dindu nuffin\"\u2014a [[Corruption (linguistic)|bastardization]] of \"didn't do nothing\"\u2014in reference to claims of innocence by arrested African-Americans. On this basis, alt-rightists referred to black people as \"dindus\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=82}}<ref name=\"Caffier\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/get-to-know-the-memes-of-the-alt-right-and-never-miss-a-dog-whistle-again |title=Get to Know the Memes of the Alt-Right and Never Miss a Dog-Whistle Again |last=Caffier |first=Justin |date=January 25, 2017 |website=Vice |accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref> Events involving black people were called \"chimpouts\", rhetorically linking them with [[chimpanzees]].{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=79\u201380}} Alt-rightists also used memes to ironically support the [[Black Egyptian hypothesis]], often using stereotypical [[African American Vernacular English|African-American vernacular]] such as \"We wuz kangz n shieet\" (\"We was kings and shit\").<ref name=\"Caffier\"/> Refugees were often referred to as \"rapefugees\", a reference to incidents like the [[2015\u201316 New Year's Eve sexual assaults in Germany]] in which non-white refugees were reported to have sexually assaulted white women.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=98\u201399}}\nAnother meme the alt-right employed was to place [[triple parentheses]] around Jewish names; this started at ''The Right Stuff'' as part of an attempt to raise awareness of the presence of Jewish Americans in the media and academia.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=83|2a1=Pollard|2y=2018|2p=77|3a1=Wendling|3y=2018|3pp=82\u201383}}<ref name=\"WPechoes\">{{cite news |last=Ohlheiser |first=Abby |title=Anti-Semitic Trump supporters made a giant list of people to target with a racist meme |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2016/06/03/anti-semitic-trump-supporters-made-a-giant-list-of-people-to-target-with-a-racist-meme/ |website=The Washington Post |date=June 3, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Caffier\"/> One alt-rightist created a [[Google Chrome]] plug in that would highlight Jewish names online.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=83}} Homosexuals and whites who socialised with people of colour were often labelled \"degenerates\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=82}}\n\nAlt-rightists often utilised older white nationalist slogans, such as the Fourteen Words: \"We must secure the existence of our people and a future for white children\",{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=76}} that \"Anti-racist is a code for anti-white\",{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=77}} and that \"Diversity is a code word for white genocide\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=78}} From the latter, alt-rightists produced the hashtag reduction \"#WhiteGenocide\" for use on Twitter, highway billboards, and flyers.{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=256}} Also used was the slogan \"[[It's OK to be white]]\" as a way of expressing a supposed reverse racism towards white people by minorities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsweek.com/neo-nazi-david-duke-backed-meme-was-reported-tucker-carlson-without-context-714655|title=The 'It's Okay to Be White' meme was backed by neo-Nazis and David Duke |date=November 19, 2017 |last=Hayden |first=Michael Edison |website=Newsweek |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> The use of \"[[Deus vult|Deus Vult]]!\" and various other [[Crusades|crusader]] iconography was employed to express Islamophobic sentiment.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/get-to-know-the-memes-of-the-alt-right-and-never-miss-a-dog-whistle-again |title=Get to Know the Memes of the Alt-Right and Never Miss a Dog-Whistle Again |last=Caffier |first=Justin |date=January 25, 2017 |website=VICE|accessdate=June 5, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/2/10/14560050/for-honor-deus-vult |title=For Honor's accidental alt-right connection |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=February 10, 2017 |website=Polygon |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170610185220/https://www.polygon.com/2017/2/10/14560050/for-honor-deus-vult |archive-date=June 10, 2017 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/01/medieval-memes |title=The far right's new fascination with the Middle Ages |author=S.N. |date=January 2, 2017 |work=The Economist |accessdate=June 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170102161443/http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2017/01/medieval-memes |archive-date=January 2, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also apparent were \"helicopter ride\" memes, which endorse documented cases of leftists being [[Death flight|dropped from helicopters]] by [[Government Junta of Chile (1973)|Chilean]] and [[National Reorganization Process|Argentine]] juntas. Similarly the term \"Right-Wing Death Squad\" (usually abbreviated as RWDS) also callbacks to the \"helicopter ride\" meme and to refer to far-right, fascist death squads.<ref name=\"Caffier\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://prospect.org/article/gop-reconsiders-trump-standard-bearer-candidate-retweets-white-supremacist |title=As GOP Reconsiders Trump as Standard Bearer |last=Stan |first=Adele M. |date=April 20, 2016 |website=The American Prospect |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\nAdditional online features of the alt-right included references to [[Fashwave]], a neo-fascist subgenre of [[electronic music]] [[microgenre]] [[vaporwave]].{{sfn|Love|2017|p=268}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/mgwk7b/fashwave-trumpwave-far-right-appropriating-electronic-music |title=Trumpwave and Fashwave Are Just the Latest Disturbing Examples of the Far-Right Appropriating Electronic Music |first1=Penn |last1=Bullock |first2=Eli |last2=Kerry |website=Vice |date=January 30, 2017 |accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Harassment ===\nWendling noted that campaigns of abuse for political ends were \"a classic alt-right tactic\",{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=131}} while Hawley called the alt-right \"a subset of the larger Internet troll culture\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=73}} Those most regularly targeted were Jewish journalists, mainstream conservative journalists, and celebrities who publicly criticized Trump.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=88}} Such harassment was usually spontaneous rather than pre-planned, but in various cases many alt-right piled on once the harassment had begun.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=87}} The conservative journalist [[David A. French]]\u2014who is white\u2014received much abuse referencing [[Nancy French|his white wife]] and adopted black daughter after criticizing Trump and the alt-right. Alt-right trolls sent him images of his daughter in a gas chamber, \"with a smiling Trump in a Nazi uniform preparing to press a button and kill her\", and repeatedly claimed that he liked to watch his wife have sex with \"black bucks\".{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=15}}\n\n''The Daily Stormer'' for instance targeted the British Member of Parliament (MP) [[Luciana Berger]], who is Jewish, by encouraging its followers to send her photoshopped images in which [[Yellow badge#Nazi Germany and Axis Powers|a yellow star]] appeared on her head; the hashtag \"Hitlerwasright\" also featured on the images.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=131}} Anglin termed this program of harassment \"Operation: Filthy Jew Bitch\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=132}} One UK-based alt-rightist was arrested and convicted for his involvement in the campaign.<ref>{{cite web |title=Racist troll guilty of harassing Labour MP with antisemitic posts |date=December 7, 2016 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/dec/07/racist-troll-guilty-harassing-labour-mp-luciana-berger-joshua-bonehill-paine }}</ref> In another instance, Anglin commented on [[Murder of Jo Cox|the June 2016 murder]] of the British MP [[Jo Cox]] by a far-right activist by saying that \"Jo Cox was evil and she deserved to die. Her death was not a tragedy, it was justice.\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=138}} While celebrating violence, ''The Daily Stormer'' is cautious to remain on the legal side of U.S. incitement laws.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=138}}\n\nIn December 2016, the artist [[Arrington de Dionyso]], whose murals are frequently displayed at the [[Comet Ping Pong]] pizzeria, described the alt-right's on-line campaign of harassment against him. He averred of the attacks in general: \"I think it's a very deliberate assault, which will eventually be a coordinated assault on all forms of free expression\".<ref name=\"Arrington de Dionyso essay.\">{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@arringtond/how-i-became-a-target-of-the-alt-right-66f14eceaffe |title=How I became a target of the alt-right: What it's like to be targeted by Neo-Nazis and supporters of Donald Trump online\u2014and what I learned from it |last=de Dionyso |first=Arrington |date=December 13, 2016 |website=Medium |accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> The [[Pizzagate conspiracy theory]] which inspired said harassment has drawn comparisons with the [[Gamergate controversy]].<ref name=\"Arrington de Dionyso interview\">{{cite web |url=http://hyperallergic.com/347458/artist-targeted-by-pizzagate-conspiracy-theory-speaks/ |title=Artist Targeted by #Pizzagate Conspiracy Theory Speaks: &nbsp;After being dragged into one of 2016's strangest news stories over a mural he made six years ago, Arrington de Dionyso took a public stand against far-right extremists' mob censorship |last=Murphy |first=Blair |date=December 22, 2016 |website=Hyperallergic |accessdate=March 20, 2019}}</ref> [[2017 Jewish Community Center bomb threats|A wave of threats]] against [[Jewish Community Center]]s starting in 2017 were blamed on the alt-right in a January 2017 article by ''[[Slate (website)|Slate]]''{{'}}s Elissa Strauss, who said members of the alt-right viewed them as \"a practical joke\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Strauss |first1=Elissa |title=The JCC Bomb Threats Confirm That Jewish Parents Are Right to Be Afraid |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/xx_factor/2017/01/19/the_jcc_bomb_threats_confirm_that_jewish_parents_are_right_to_be_afraid.html |accessdate=March 23, 2017 |work=Slate |date=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe anonymized and decentralized nature of the alt-right makes it difficult to determine how many individuals are involved in it or the demographic attributes of this membership.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=77}} The movement's members are concentrated in the United States, but with participants present in other Anglophone countries like Canada, Britain, and Australia, as well as in parts of continental Europe.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=8}} The movement is majority male,{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=149}}<ref name=\"AtlanticWomen\"/> although Hawley suggested that about 20% of its support might be female.<ref name=\"AtlanticWomen\"/>\n\nFrom the nature of the online discourse as well as the attendees of events organized by NPI and American Renaissance, Hawley believed that the majority of alt-right participants are younger on average than the participants of most previous American far-right groups.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=77}} Spencer suggested that \"if we were to make a composite image of the Alt-Right, I would probably say someone who is thirty years old, who is a tech professional, who is an atheist, and who lives on one of the coasts.\"{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=78}} Wendling however suggested that \"the alt-right's self-image of themselves as a force made up of ranks of hipsterish, erudite well-educated men is misleading\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=131}} In contrast to the movement's self-presentation as \"a cool posse of young intelligent kids\", through his research he found that many of those active on alt-right forums were middle-aged men from working-class backgrounds.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=146}}\n\n[[File:White supremacist (35782612633).jpg|thumb|right|An attendee at the Unite the Right rally carrying a firearm and wearing a Confederate Battle Flag T-shirt.]]\n\nOn interviewing young members of the alt-right, Hawley noted that many articulated the common theme, stating that they embraced far-right politics in response to the growing racial polarisation of the Obama era, in particular the public debates around the shootings of [[Trayvon Martin]] and [[Shooting of Michael Brown|Michael Brown]] and the rise of the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=78}} Hawley suggested that many of these young people were willing to embrace the idea of dismantling the United States in favour of a new, [[white ethno-state]] because they had grown up in the U.S. during the post-civil rights era. In contrast, he thought, older white nationalists were keener to retain links to patriotic American imagery because they nostalgically recalled a period of U.S. history when segregation and overt white dominance were a part of life and believed that this system could be reinstated.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=80\u201381}}\n\nWendling believed that a large portion of the alt-right were university students or recent graduates, many bearing a particular grudge against political correctness.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=8}} The alt-right ideologue Greg Johnson suggested that the alt-right was drawing in better educated people than previous white nationalist movements because the career prospects for college-educated European Americans had declined by the late 2000s. Whereas a college degree was previously perceived as a guaranteed ticket to a middle-class lifestyle, he noted that this was no longer the case and that many college and university educated people felt resentful and, due to unemployment or underemployment, had growing amounts of time on their hands which they could spend on the Internet.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=78\u201379}}\n\nYiannopoulos claimed that some \"young rebels\" are drawn to the alt-right not for deeply political reasons, but \"because it promises fun, transgression, and a challenge to social norms\". According to ''The New Yorker'', \"testing the strength of the speech taboos that revolve around conventional politics-of what can be said, and how directly\" is a major component of alt-right identity. The beliefs that make the alt-right perceptible as a movement \"are in their essence not matters of substance but of style\" and the alt-right's tone may just be concealing \"a more familiar politics\".<ref>{{cite article |last=Wallace-Wells |first=Benjamin |date=May 5, 2016 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/benjamin-wallace-wells/is-the-alt-right-for-real |title=Is the Alt-Right for Real? |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA research study of 447 self-identified alt-right members found higher levels of dark triad traits compared to the general population; and that members of the alt-right were more likely to express prejudice against black people and admit to engaging in aggressive behavior. Alt-right members also had significantly high levels of dehumanization, with the mean alt-right scores comparable to how the general public views the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]. Alt-right members viewed Hillary Clinton, Muslims, feminists, Nigerians and journalists as the least well rated groups on the dehumanization scale while white people, men and Americans were rated the best.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vox.com/platform/amp/science-and-health/2017/8/15/16144070/psychology-alt-right |title=Psychologists surveyed hundreds of alt-right supporters. The results are unsettling. |website=Vox |accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Causal factors ===\n\nThe scholar of [[American studies]] Annie Kelly argued that the alt-right was \"both inspired and defined by a discourse of anxiety about traditional white masculinity\", a discourse which was \"dominant in much of the political and cultural mainstream\". In her view, much of the \"groundwork\" for this discourse was set forth by the conservative movement in the years following the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001.{{sfn|Kelly|2017|p=69}} Hawley concurred that American conservatism was \"at least somewhat responsible for the rise of the Alt-Right\" because some individuals within the conservative movement, such as [[Ann Coulter]], had \"effectively delegitimized complaints about hate speech and racism\" as part of their attacks on political correctness in the years before the alt-right's appearance.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=44}} This is something acknowledged by some conservatives, like columnist [[Matt K. Lewis]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=44\u201345}}\n\nCommentator [[Angela Nagle]] said that a mainstream \"alt-light\" more interested in performance than political goals helped the alt-right in its rise, saying that should the alt-right grow to generate great violence, those on the right who helped to make the alt-right look attractive, such as Yiannopoulos, \"will have to take responsibility for having played their role\" in enabling its growth.{{sfn|Nagle|2017|p=9}} She also suggested that \"the hysterical liberal call-out\" culture of the 2010s, in which \"everyone from saccharine pop stars to [[Justin Trudeau]] [was called] a 'white supremacist' and everyone who wasn't [[2016 United States presidential election#Notable expressions, phrases, and statements|With Her]] a sexist\" made it more difficult for people to recognize when a far-right movement really emerged online; she compared the situation with the tale of [[The Boy Who Cried Wolf]].{{sfn|Nagle|2017|pp=8\u20139}} Disagreeing with Nagle's view that the alt-right was primarily a \"response to the stupidity of marginal Internet liberalism\", the anti-fascist reporter Jay Firestone\u2014who had spent three months undercover in New York's alt-right community\u2014instead argued that it was a \"response to decades of decline in standards of living for working people, amid the proliferation of unemployment and meaningless, dead-end jobs.\"<ref>{{cite article |last=Firestone |first=Jay |title=Three Months Inside Alt-Right New York |website=Commune |date=Spring 2019 |url=https://communemag.com/alt-right-new-york/ |accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist Philip W. Gray cited several reasons for the emergence of the alt-right. In his analysis, new online media had reduced the conservative movement's ability to enforce its boundaries against the far right, while the growing distance of the Second World War meant that pride in the U.S. victory over Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy provided less of a barrier to the American far-right than it had when there were still large numbers of people who remembered the conflict.{{sfn|Gray|2018|pp=151\u2013152}} Gray also argued that the alt-right was a reaction against the left-wing racial and social agitation of the 2010s, in particular the Black Lives Matter movement and the popularisation of concepts like [[white privilege]] and [[male privilege]], as well as events like the racial unrest in [[2015 Baltimore protests|Baltimore]] and [[Ferguson unrest|Ferguson]] and the shooting of police officers in [[2016 shooting of Dallas police officers|Dallas]] and [[2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers|Baton Rouge]].{{sfn|Gray|2018|pp=152\u2013153}}\n\n== Links to violence and terrorism ==\n{{quote box\n|quote=The sprawling networks the alt-right has built around its poisonous, racist ideology have violence at its core in its pursuit of a white ethnostate. The white, male grievance culture that the leaders of the alt-right are incubating has already inspired more than 40 deaths and left more than 60 people injured.\n\nAnd unfortunately, the alt-right seems likely to inspire more, as it moves further into the real world. Its leaders continue to abdicate all responsibility for the violence their ideology inspires and are becoming increasingly recalcitrant in the face of widespread condemnation.\n\n... After a year [2017] of escalating alt-right violence, we are probably in for more.\n|source= \u2014The Southern Poverty Law Center, 2018<ref name=splc2018/>\n|align=rightt\n|width=30%\n|style=padding:8px;\n|bgcolor = #CCDDFF\n}}\nIn 2017, Hawley noted that the alt-right was not a violent movement, but that this could potentially change.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=170}} From their analysis of online discourse, Phillips and Yi concluded that \"rather than violence, most Alt-Right members focus on discussing and peacefully advocating their values\".{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=224}} They added that presenting the alt-right as a violent, revolutionary movement, or equating all alt-rightists with the 1488 scene, was \"an intellectual failure akin to treating all Muslims or black nationalists as radicals and terrorists\", also noting that it served as a \"rhetorical tactic\" for progressives.{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=224}}\n\nConversely, Wending noted that there were individuals on the extreme end of the alt-right willing to use violence.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=12}} He stated that \"the culture of the alt-right is breeding its own brand of terrorists: socially isolated young men who are willing to kill.\"{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=173}} The alt-right movement has been considered by some political researchers a terrorist movement and the process of alt-right radicalization has been compared to Islamic terrorism by [[political scientists]] and leaders.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/opinion/university-virginia-uva-protests-charlottesville.html |title=What U.Va. Students Saw in Charlottesville|date=August 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=January 14, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/blue-ridge-caucus-mark-warner-calls-members-of-alt-right/article_74f2f17b-f3c5-5a04-be7f-47a4abba7534.html |title=Blue Ridge Caucus: Mark Warner calls members of Alt-Right 'domestic terrorists' after Charlottesville rally |first=Carmen |last=Forman |work=Roanoke Times|accessdate=January 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://faithfullymagazine.com/unite-right-hate-rally-charlottesville-terrorism/ |title=Unite the Right Hate Rally in Charlottesville Is an Act of Terrorism|author=Kyle J. Howard |date=August 12, 2017 |work=Faithfully Magazine |accessdate=January 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://aeon.co/amp/essays/radical-islam-and-the-alt-right-are-not-so-different |title=Alt-Right or jihad?|author=Scott Atran |work=Aeon|accessdate=January 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/12/19/16764046/islam-terrorism-far-right-extremism-isis |title=Reciprocal rage: why Islamist extremists and the far right need each other|author=Sean Illing |work=Vox|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=January 14, 2018}}</ref> A paper on the subject stated that it clearly fell under an [[Extremist Groups|extremist movement]], saying that \"alt-right adherents also expressed hostility that could be considered extremist: they were quite willing to blatantly dehumanize both religious/national outgroups and political opposition groups\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2017/08/16/the-alt-right-is-just-another-word-for-white-supremacy-study-finds/ |title=Analysis {{!}} The 'alt-right' is just another word for white supremacy, study finds|last=Ingraham|first=Christopher|date=August 16, 2017|work=Washington Post|accessdate=January 15, 2018|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n===Violent incidents===\n\nIn February 2018, the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] assembled a list of 13 violent incidents between 2014 and 2018 perpetrated by alt-right influenced people, in which 43 people died and 67 people were injured. The perpetrators of these events were all white men between the ages of 17 and 37, with an average age of just over 25 years old (only three of them were over 30). All but one was American, the other was Canadian.<ref name=splc2018>{{cite website |date=February 5, 2018 |url=https://www.splcenter.org/20180205/alt-right-killing-people |title=The Alt-Right is Killing People |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n[[Dylann Roof]] spent much time reading alt-right websites before carrying out the 2015 [[Charleston church shooting]],{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=258}} however he took greater interest in older white nationalist writers and groups, like the [[Council of Conservative Citizens]] and the [[Northwest Front]].{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=12}}\nIn December 2017, the 21-year old William Edward Atchison [[Aztec High School shooting|shot dead two students]] at [[Aztec High School]] in [[Aztec, New Mexico|Aztec]], [[New Mexico]] before killing himself. Atchison's online activity had included posting pro-Hitler and pro-Trump thoughts on alt-right websites like ''The Daily Stormer'' under such usernames as \"Future Mass Shooter\" and \"[[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Adam Lanza]]\" and joking about school shootings, in particular the [[Columbine High School massacre]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dupuy |first=Beatrice |date=December 15, 2017 |title=White Man Behind School Shooting Was Obsessed With Trump and Hitler |url=http://www.newsweek.com/william-atchison-led-double-life-online-749363 |work=[[Newsweek]] |location= |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Preza |first=Elizabeth |date=December 15, 2017 |title=New Mexico school shooter was radicalized on white supremacist pro-Trump websites |url=https://www.rawstory.com/2017/12/new-mexico-school-shooter-was-radicalized-on-white-supremacist-pro-trump-websites/ |work=Raw Story |location=|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn alt-righter named Taylor Wilson who had attended the Unite the Right Rally was charged with attempting a terror attack on an [[Amtrak]] train in October 2017. It was reported that he held a business card from the American-based neo-Nazi political party [[National Socialist Movement (United States)|National Socialist Movement]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/white-supremacist-accused-amtrak-terror-attack-also-attended-alt-right-event-771495 |title=Amtrak terror suspect also attended \"alt-right\" event in Charlottesville, according to FBI |date=January 4, 2018 |work=Newsweek|accessdate=January 14, 2018 }}</ref>\nIn October 2018, Robert Bowers [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting|opened fire on a synagogue in Pittsburgh]], killing 11 and injuring 6. He was a member of a fringe social network called [[Gab (social network)|Gab]], where he posted a message indicating an immediate intent to harm just prior to the shooting; Bowers had a history of extreme antisemitic postings on Gab.<ref name=nyt20181028>{{cite news |last=Roose |first=Kevin |date=28 October 2018 |title=On Gab, an Extremist-Friendly Site, Pittsburgh Shooting Suspect Aired His Hatred in Full |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/28/us/gab-robert-bowers-pittsburgh-synagogue-shootings.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref> The website is a favorite of alt-right users who are banned or suspended from other social networks.<ref name=hill_2017-08-18>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/technology/347106-citing-hate-speech-google-suspends-social-media-site-favored-by-alt-right|title=Citing hate speech, Google suspends social media site favored by alt-right from app store|last=Neidig|first=Harper|date=2017-08-18|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"verge_2018-10-27\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/27/18032930/paypal-banned-gab-following-pittsburgh-shooting|title=Paypal bans Gab following Pittsburgh shooting|last1=Liptak|first1=Andrew|publisher=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=October 27, 2018|date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nVarious far-right militant groups have been linked with the alt-right. The [[Rise Above Movement]] (RAM), based in Southern California, has been linked to various violent acts, including participation in the Unite the Right rally. According to Oren Segal, director of the Anti-Defamation League's Center on Extremism, RAM constituted \"an alt-right street-fighting club\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/white-hate-group-campaign-of-menace-rise-above-movement |title=Racist, violent, unpunished: A white hate group's campaign of menace |date=October 19, 2017 |website=ProPublica |others=A.C. Thompson, Ali Winston, Darwin BondGraham|accessdate=January 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFar-right groups outside the U.S. have also been influenced by the alt-right. ''The Stawell-Times News'' noted that [[Antipodean Resistance]], an Australian neo-Nazi group, had links to the alt-right online subculture.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.stawelltimes.com.au/story/4971439/neo-nazi-grampians-camp-used-for-recruitment/ |title=Neo-Nazi Grampians camp used for recruitment |last=Martinich |first=Rex |date=October 6, 2017 |work=The Stawell Times-News|accessdate=December 27, 2017 }}</ref> The group, which makes use of Nazi symbols such as the [[swastika]] and the [[Nazi salute]], has explicitly called for the legalisation of the murder of Jews.<ref>{{cite web |date=April 20, 2017 |first=Eden |last=Faithfull |url=http://www.usu.edu.au/News/White-Supremacist-Neo-Nazi-Group-Propaganda-Found.aspx |title=White Supremacist Neo-Nazi Propaganda Found on Sydney University Campus |website=usu.edu.au |publisher=[[University of Sydney Union]] |accessdate=September 5, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905094151/http://www.usu.edu.au/News/White-Supremacist-Neo-Nazi-Group-Propaganda-Found.aspx |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.jewishnews.net.au/hatred-on-our-doorsteps/67585 |newspaper=[[Australian Jewish News]] |title=Hatred on our doorsteps |date=August 17, 2017 |accessdate=September 5, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-date=September 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905095020/https://www.jewishnews.net.au/hatred-on-our-doorsteps/67585 }}</ref> The group was initially involved in vandalism and organising training camps, although various commentators warned that it might turn to terrorism and should be proscribed.<ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-05/neo-nazi-group-antipodean-resistance/8852682 |title=Antipodean Resistance Neo-Nazi group trying to sway Australia's same-sex marriage postal vote |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=September 5, 2017 |first=Danny |last=Tran |accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Atomwaffen Division ====\n{{main|Atomwaffen Division}}\nThe Atomwaffen Division (''Atomwaffen'' meaning \"atomic weapons\" in [[German language|German]]) is a [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] [[terrorism|terrorist]] organization based in the United States. Founded in 2013 on the now defunct neo-fascist forum Iron March, the group's main base of operations is in [[Florida]], but has members in other states such as Texas and [[Montana]]. The group is part of the alt-right,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2018/01/29/suspect-penn-student-murder-neo-nazi-ties/|title=Report: Suspect in Penn Student's Murder Has Neo-Nazi Ties|date=January 29, 2018|work=Philadelphia Magazine|accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"HuffPostAttomwaffen\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/alt-right-charles-manson-atomwaffen_us_5a146921e4b03dec824892e6|title=The Maniac Neo-Nazis Keeping Charles Manson's Race War Alive |last=Mathias |first=Christopher |date=November 21, 2017|website=|accessdate=October 28, 2018|quote=Even within the alt-right \u2014 a loose association of white supremacists and fascists \u2014 the Atomwaffen Division is considered extreme.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/atomwaffen-nazi-murder-bomb-plot_us_5a70825ae4b00d0de2240328|title=1 Neo-Nazi Group. 5 Murders In 8 Months.|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=January 23, 2018|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=February 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mayo\">{{cite web|author=Marilyn Mayo|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/alt-right-groups-target-campuses-with-fliers|title=Alt Right Groups Target Campuses with Fliers|publisher=Anti-Defamation League|date=December 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"FlieringCollege\">{{Cite press release|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-white-supremacist-group-redoubling-hate-fliering-efforts-on-campus|title=ADL: White Supremacist Group Redoubling Hate Fliering Efforts on Campus|publisher=Anti-Defamation League|date=September 11, 2017}}</ref> but is considered extreme even within that movement.<ref name=\"HuffPostAttomwaffen\" /> It encourages members to [[Flag desecration|burn the United States flag]] and the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]], and to attack the U.S. government and minorities (especially [[Jews]]).<ref name=\"Atomwaffen\" /> The group, whose members are mostly young white males, has been active on [[university campus]]es recruitment postering. The [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], Texas, chapter is listed as a [[hate group]] by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Active Hate Groups 2016|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2017/active-hate-groups-2016|accessdate=August 8, 2017|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|date=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"phillips\">{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Kristine|title=A neo-Nazi with explosives and a framed photo of Timothy McVeigh is not a threat, judge rules|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2017/06/11/a-neo-nazi-with-explosives-and-a-framed-photo-of-timothy-mcveigh-is-not-a-threat-judge-rules/|accessdate=August 8, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=June 11, 2017}}</ref> ''Atomwaffen'' has engaged in plans to cripple public water systems and destroy parts of the American [[Continental U.S. power transmission grid|electric grid]]. Atomwaffen has also been accused of plans to blow up nuclear plants to cause [[Nuclear meltdown|meltdowns]] of American nuclear energy sites.<ref name=\"Atomwaffen\" /> The organization aims for a violent overthrow of the United States government by use of terrorism and [[guerrilla warfare]] tactics. Since 2017, the organization has been linked to eight killings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/atomwaffen-division-awd|title=Backgrounder: Atomwaffen Division (AWD)|publisher=Anti-Defamation Leagueaccessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Swenson, Kyle (January 29, 2018) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2018/01/29/suspects-in-five-homicides-reportedly-tied-to-macabre-neo-nazi-group/ \"Suspects in five killings reportedly linked to macabre neo-Nazi group\"] ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/psychedelic-nazis-prosecutors-say-member-of-white-supremacist-group-involved-with-illegal-guns-drugs/2019/09/20/8a41c880-dbbf-11e9-a688-303693fb4b0b_story.html | title=Prosecutors say an alleged member of a white-supremacist group was involved with illegal guns, drugs | work=[[Washington Post]] | date=September 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://ent.siteintelgroup.com/Far-Right-/-Far-Left-Threat/soldier-charged-with-distributing-bomb-making-information-claimed-ties-to-atomwaffen-members-sought-to-kill-every-last-jew-across-the-world.html | title=Soldier Charged With Distributing Bomb Making Information Claimed Ties To Atomwaffen Members, Sought \"To Kill...Every Last Jew Across the World\" | work=[[SITE Intelligence Group]] | date=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.winknews.com/2019/09/25/two-former-army-soldiers-charged-with-double-murder-in-fort-myers/ | title=Two former US Army soldiers indicted for 2018 Estero double-murder | work=[[WINK-TV]] | date=September 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.rt.com/usa/469428-us-soldier-arrested-azov-battalion/ | title=US soldier arrested for plot to bomb news network planned to fight with Azov Battalion in Ukraine | work=[[Russia Today]] | date=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/1-killed-in-fairfax-county-shooting-suspect-in-custody-police-say | title=1 killed in Fairfax County shooting, suspect in custody, police say | work=[[Fox News]] | date=September 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe leader of Atomwaffen Division, Brandon Russell, is alleged to have described [[Omar Mateen]], who pledged allegiance to ISIS and perpetrated the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], as \"a hero\". A member of Atomwaffen Division, Stephen Billingsley, was photographed at a vigil in San Antonio, Texas for the victims of the Orlando shooting with a skull mask and a sign saying \"God Hates Fags\".<ref name=\"SPLC2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/06/20/donning-mask-presenting-face-21st-century-fascism |title=Donning the Mask: Presenting 'The Face of 21st Century Fascism' |date=June 20, 2017 |work=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=August 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/news_columnists/brian_chasnoff/article/Racist-at-vigil-sends-online-message-8310166.php |title=Racist at vigil sends online message |last1=Chasnoff |first1=Brian |date=June 17, 2016 |work=Express News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://radaronline.com/celebrity-news/neo-nazi-group-atomwaffen-division-targets-us-college-students/ |title=Neo-Nazi Nerds Recruiting Students At Top Universities To Carry Out ISIS Attacks |date=January 17, 2017 |work=Radar Online}}</ref><ref name=\"huff\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/neo-nazis-isis-devon-arthurs_us_5925cd0ae4b00c8df2a13b18 |title=The Enemy Of My Enemy Is My Friend: What Neo-Nazis Like About ISIS |last1=Matthias |first1=Christopher |date=May 26, 2017 |work=Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Atomwaffen Division member Devon Arthurs killed two fellow members, Jeremy Himmelman and Andrew Oneschuk, after they ridiculed his conversion to [[Salafi jihadism|Salafi jihadi]] [[Islam]]; he called himself a \"Salafist National Socialist\". Arthurs was then arrested following a hostage situation.<ref name=\"huff\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vb4n8a/gruesome-florida-murders-show-how-neo-nazis-turn-into-jihadists |title=Gruesome Florida Murders Show How Neo-Nazis Turn into Jihadists |last1=Conti |first1=Allie |date=May 25, 2017 |work=Vice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/ellievhall/former-neo-nazi-allegedly-kills-roommates |title=A Neo-Nazi Who Converted To Islam Allegedly Killed His Roommates Over Religion |last1=Hall |first1=Ellie |date=May 23, 2017 |work=BuzzFeed}}</ref> Another member, Brandon Russell, was then arrested; in his garage was found the explosive compound [[hexamethylene triperoxide diamine]] and in his bedroom was a framed photograph of [[Timothy McVeigh]], the perpetrator of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rawstory.com/2017/05/fbi-busts-atomwaffen-neo-nazi-in-florida-for-making-explosives-and-finds-radioactive-materials/ |title=FBI busts 'Atomwaffen' Neo-Nazi in Florida for making explosives \u2014 and finds radiation materials |last1=Al-Sibai |first1=Noor |date=May 22, 2017 |work=RawStory}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tbo.com/news/military/how-did-florida-national-guard-miss-soldiers-neo-nazi-leanings/2324930 |title=How did Florida National Guard miss soldier's neo-Nazi leanings? |last1=Altman |first1=Howard |date=May 23, 2017 |work=TBO}}</ref> In January 2018, the Atomwaffen Division member Samuel Woodward was charged in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], California with killing [[Blaze Bernstein]], a gay Jewish college student.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thompson|first1=A.C.|last2=Winston|first2=Ali|last3=Hanrahan|first3=Jake|title=California Murder Suspect Said to Have Trained With Extremist Hate Group \u2014 ProPublica|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/california-murder-suspect-atomwaffen-division-extremist-hate-group|accessdate=January 27, 2018|work=ProPublica|date=January 26, 2018}}</ref> Bernstein's was the fifth killing tied to the Atomwaffen group.<ref name=\"Atomwaffen\">{{cite news|title=Inside Atomwaffen As It Celebrates a Member for Allegedly Killing a Gay Jewish College Student |publisher= |website=ProPublica |first1=A.C.| last1=Thompson |first2=Ali |last2=Winston |first3=Jake |last3=Hanrahan |date=February 23, 2018 |url=https://www.propublica.org/article/atomwaffen-division-inside-white-hate-group |accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Unite the Right rally ====\n{{main|Unite the Right rally}}\n[[File:2017 Charlottesville vehicle-ramming attack.webm|thumb|Video of the vehicular ramming that killed one person and injured 19.]]\n\nAfter the aborted rally at around 1:45&nbsp;p.m.,<ref name=\"maggie\">{{cite news |first=Maggie |last=Astor |title=A Guide to the Charlottesville Aftermath |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/charlottesville-virginia-overview.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814223430/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/charlottesville-virginia-overview.html |archivedate=August 14, 2017}}</ref> a man drove his car into a crowd of counter protesters, hitting several and slamming into a stopped sedan, which hit a stopped minivan that was in front of it. The impact of the crash pushed the sedan and the minivan further into the crowd. One person was killed and 19 others were injured in what police have called a [[vehicle-ramming attack|deliberate attack]]. The man then reversed the car through the crowd and fled the scene.<ref name=\"FieldsWhatWeKnow\">{{cite news |author=Jonah Engel Bromwich & Alan Blinder |title=What We Know About James Alex Fields, Driver Charged in Charlottesville Killing |date=August 13, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/james-alex-fields-charlottesville-driver-.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813205813/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/james-alex-fields-charlottesville-driver-.html |archivedate=August 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Nick Penzenstadler |date=August 13, 2017 |title=Heather Heyer: Community mourns woman killed in Charlottesville attack |newspaper=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/08/13/heather-heyer-community-mourns-woman-killed-charlottesville-attack/562776001/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813210159/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/08/13/heather-heyer-community-mourns-woman-killed-charlottesville-attack/562776001/ |archivedate=August 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/12/us/charlottesville-car-crash-suspect-idd/index.html |title=Charlottesville car crash suspect ID'd as 20-year-old Ohio man |author=Chuck Johnston |website=CNN |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813011757/http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/12/us/charlottesville-car-crash-suspect-idd/index.html |archivedate=August 13, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe ramming occurred at a pedestrian mall at Water and Fourth streets, about four blocks away from Emancipation Park ({{coord|38|01|46.17|N|78|28|46.29|W|display=inline}}).<ref name=\"ShapiroSilverman\">T. Rees Shapiro, Ellie Silverman, Laura Vozzella and John Woodrow Cox, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/one-dead-as-car-strikes-crowds-amid-protests-of-white-nationalist-gathering-in-charlottesville-two-police-die-in-helicopter-crash/2017/08/13/3590b3ce-8021-11e7-902a-2a9f2d808496_story.html Alleged driver of car that plowed into Charlottesville crowd was a Nazi sympathizer, former teacher says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814011801/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/one-dead-as-car-strikes-crowds-amid-protests-of-white-nationalist-gathering-in-charlottesville-two-police-die-in-helicopter-crash/2017/08/13/3590b3ce-8021-11e7-902a-2a9f2d808496_story.html|date=August 14, 2017}}, ''The Washington Post'' (August 13, 2017).</ref> Heather D. Heyer, a 32-year-old paralegal from Charlottesville, was fatally injured in the attack and pronounced dead at the [[University of Virginia Health System|University of Virginia's University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obituary: Heather Heyer died on August 12th |url=https://www.economist.com/news/obituary/21726701-legal-assistant-killed-far-right-rally-charlottesville-was-32-obituary-heather |accessdate=August 18, 2017 |work=[[The Economist]] |date=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.vice.com/story/heather-heyer-charlottesville-car-attack |title=Heather Heyer identified as victim of Charlottesville car attack |website=vice.com |accessdate=August 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816064702/https://news.vice.com/story/heather-heyer-charlottesville-car-attack |archivedate=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Heather Heyer, Charlottesville Victim, Is Recalled as a 'Strong Woman' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/heather-heyer-charlottesville-victim.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 13, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816235535/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/13/us/heather-heyer-charlottesville-victim.html |archivedate=August 16, 2017}}</ref> Video footage recorded at the scene showed a gray 2010 [[Dodge Challenger]] accelerating towards crowds on a pedestrian mall, hitting people and sending them airborne, then reversing at high speed, hitting more people.<ref name=\"HeimWaPo\">Heim, Joe; Silverman, Ellie; Shapiro, T. Rees; & Brown, Emma (August 12, 2017) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/fights-in-advance-of-saturday-protest-in-charlottesville/2017/08/12/155fb636-7f13-11e7-83c7-5bd5460f0d7e_story.html \"One dead as car strikes crowds amid protests of white nationalist gathering in Charlottesville; two police die in helicopter crash\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref> The moment when the car was driven into the crowd was captured on video by bystanders and in [[Aerial photography|aerial video footage]] taken by a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]].<ref>Joseph A. Wulfsohn, [https://www.mediaite.com/online/drone-footage-captured-the-terrifying-moment-james-fields-drove-into-a-crowd-in-charlottesville/ Drone Footage Captured the Terrifying Moment James Fields Drove Into a Crowd in Charlottesville] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814055252/https://www.mediaite.com/online/drone-footage-captured-the-terrifying-moment-james-fields-drove-into-a-crowd-in-charlottesville|date=August 14, 2017}}, ''Mediate'' (August 12, 2017).</ref> A photographer present at the scene said the car \"plowed into a sedan and then into a minivan. Bodies flew. People were terrified and screaming\". According to ''The Guardian'', Bystanders said it was \"definitely a violent attack\".<ref name=\"ManCharged\">{{cite news |first1=Jason |last1=Wilson |first2=Edward |last2=Helmore |first3=Jon |last3=Swaine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/aug/12/virginia-unite-the-right-rally-protest-violence |title=Charlottesville: man charged with murder after car rams counter-protesters at far-right event |work=The Guardian |date=August 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813050625/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/aug/12/virginia-unite-the-right-rally-protest-violence |archivedate=August 13, 2017}}</ref> Of the 19 injured survivors, the [[University of Virginia Health System#Components|University of Virginia Medical Center]] reported that five were initially in critical condition.<ref name=\"HeimWaPo\" /> By the afternoon of August 14, ten patients had been discharged from the hospital and the nine remaining patients were in good condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ksl.com/article/45409905/the-latest-student-leaders-say-campuses-should-be-safe|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816024144/https://www.ksl.com/?nid=151&sid=45409905&title=the-latest-10-patients-released-9-in-good-condition|url-status=dead|title=The Latest: Student leaders say campuses should be safe|archivedate=August 16, 2017|website=www.ksl.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Police block of crash site (36195158640).jpg|thumb|Police block the site of the vehicular crash.]]\n\nShortly after the collision, James Alex Fields Jr., a 20-year-old from [[Ohio]] who reportedly had expressed sympathy for Nazi Germany during his time as a student at [[Randall K. Cooper High School|Cooper High School]] in [[Union, Kentucky|Union]], Kentucky,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/13/543176250/charlottesville-attack-james-alex-fields-jr |title=Charlottesville Car Attack: Who Is Accused Suspect James Alex Fields Jr.?: The Two-Way |publisher=NPR |accessdate=August 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817000743/http://www.npr.org/2017/08/13/543176250/charlottesville-attack-james-alex-fields-jr |archivedate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> was arrested.<ref name=\"FieldsWhatWeKnow\" /><ref name=\"JohnstonSuspectIDd\">Chuck Johnston, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/12/us/charlottesville-car-crash-suspect-idd/index.html \"Charlottesville car crash suspect ID'd as 20-year-old Ohio man\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813011757/http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/12/us/charlottesville-car-crash-suspect-idd/index.html|date=August 13, 2017}}, CNN (August 12, 2017).</ref>\n\nFields had been photographed taking part in the rally, holding a shield emblazoned with the logo of [[Vanguard America]], a [[neo-Nazi]], [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]], [[white supremacist]] organization. Vanguard America's leaders later stated he was not a member and that \"[t]he shields seen do not denote membership\" as they were \"freely handed out to anyone in attendance\".<ref name=\"WaPoVanguard\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/vanguard-america-a-white-supremacist-group-denies-charlottesville-attacker-was-a-member/2017/08/15/2ec897c6-810e-11e7-8072-73e1718c524d_story.html Vanguard America, a white supremacist group, denies Charlottesville ramming suspect was a member] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816064902/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/vanguard-america-a-white-supremacist-group-denies-charlottesville-attacker-was-a-member/2017/08/15/2ec897c6-810e-11e7-8072-73e1718c524d_story.html|date=August 16, 2017}}. ''[[Washington Post]]'', August 15, 2017.</ref> On August 14, Fields was again denied bail.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sotomayor |first=Marianna |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/charlottesville-suspect-james-alex-fields-jr-denied-bond-first-court-n792381 |title=Charlottesville Suspect James Alex Fields Jr. Denied Bond at First Court Appearance |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=August 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815205641/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/charlottesville-suspect-james-alex-fields-jr-denied-bond-first-court-n792381 |archivedate=August 15, 2017}}</ref> He is being held at the [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle-Charlottesville County]] Regional Jail.<ref name=\"JohnstonSuspectIDd\" />\n\n[[National Security Adviser (United States)|National Security Adviser]] [[H. R. McMaster]] and several senators{{Who|date=October 2019}} described the alleged ramming attack as an act of [[Domestic terrorism in the United States|domestic terrorism]] as did various commentators.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/08/13/national_security_adviser_h_r_mcmaster_on_charlottesville_of_course_it_was.html |title=National Security Adviser McMaster on Charlottesville: \"Of Course it Was Terrorism\" |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=August 13, 2017 |accessdate=August 13, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814072231/http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/08/13/national_security_adviser_h_r_mcmaster_on_charlottesville_of_course_it_was.html |archivedate=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/2017/08/12/543096579/trump-saw-many-sides-while-some-republicans-saw-white-supremacy-domestic-terrori Trump Saw 'Many Sides' While Some Republicans Saw White Supremacy, Domestic Terrorism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814055853/http://www.npr.org/2017/08/12/543096579/trump-saw-many-sides-while-some-republicans-saw-white-supremacy-domestic-terrori|date=August 14, 2017}}. [[NPR]], August 12, 2017.</ref> Late on the night of August 12, former Attorney General Jeff Sessions said the Department of Justice would open a civil rights investigation into the incident, with federal investigators investigating whether the suspect \"crossed state lines with the intent to commit violence\".<ref>Joe Ruiz, [https://www.npr.org/2017/08/13/543176250/charlottesville-attack-james-alex-fields-jr \"Ohio Man Charged With Murder In Fatal Car Attack On Anti-White Nationalist March\"], ''NPR'', August 13, 2017. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813222823/http://www.npr.org/2017/08/13/543176250/charlottesville-attack-james-alex-fields-jr|date=August 13, 2017}}.</ref><ref>[http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/08/13/department_of_justice_launches_probe_into_charlottesville_violence_that.html \"Department of Justice Launches Probe Into Charlottesville Violence That Left Three Dead\"], ''Slate'', August 13, 2017. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813150123/http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/08/13/department_of_justice_launches_probe_into_charlottesville_violence_that.html|date=August 13, 2017}}, ''Slate''.</ref> Later, Sessions said the ramming meets the definition of \"domestic terrorism\" and that it was \"an unacceptable, evil attack\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-attorney-general-evil-charlottesville-car-ramming-fits/story?id=49202191 |title=Sessions defends Trump on Charlottesville, says car ramming fits 'domestic terrorism' |date=August 14, 2017 |website=ABC News |accessdate=August 14, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814182323/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-attorney-general-evil-charlottesville-car-ramming-fits/story?id=49202191 |archivedate=August 14, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nFields was charged with [[second-degree murder]], three counts of [[malicious wounding]] and [[Hit and run|failure to stop]] following an accident resulting in death and held without bail.<ref name=\"JohnstonSuspectIDd\" /><ref name=\"ManCharged\" /> On August 18, Fields was charged with three additional counts of aggravated malicious wounding and two additional counts of malicious wounding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/fields-faces-additional-felony-charges-related-to-aug-fatal-crash/article_7608f516-845d-11e7-986e-b73741c8b869.html |title=Fields faces 5 additional felony charges related to Aug. 12 fatal crash |newspaper=The Daily Progress |date=August 18, 2017}}</ref> The murder charge was changed to first-degree murder on December 14.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/driver-accused-of-plowing-into-charlottesville-crowd-killing-heather-heyer-due-in-court/2017/12/13/6cbb4ce8-e029-11e7-89e8-edec16379010_story.html |title=First-degree murder charge for driver accused of plowing into Charlottesville crowd, killing Heather Heyer |last1=Duggan |first1=Paul |date=December 14, 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |location=Charlottesville, Virginia |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, other acts of domestic violence committed at the Unite the Right rally were an [[African-Americans|African-American]] man named [[DeAndre Harris]] assaulted by white supremacist members and a [[Ku Klux Klan|Klansman]] named Richard W. Preston (an Imperial Wizard for the [[Maryland]]-based Confederate White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan) shooting a gun towards counterprotestors including Corey A. Long (who was black).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41599533 |title=Black man beaten in Charlottesville far-right rally charged |date=October 12, 2017 |accessdate=October 13, 2017 |publisher= |website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/ku-klux-klan-leader-found-guilty-for-firing-gun-at-charlottesville-rally/2018/05/08/d4229ec6-522b-11e8-9c91-7dab596e8252_story.html Ku Klux Klan leader found guilty for firing gun at Charlottesville rally], ''Washington Post'', May 8, 2018</ref> In January 2018, a court hearing was held in which November 26, 2018, was set as the date for Fields' trial to begin. Trial is anticipated to take three weeks.<ref>[http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/fields-set-for-three-week-trial-in-november/article_d497a604-f0be-11e7-bc83-f7eff49a1576.html \"Fields set for three-week trial in November\"], ''Daily Progress'', January 3, 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring the rally, Vasillios Pistolis, a U.S. Marine and a member of the terrorist group [[Atomwaffen Division]], was recorded chanting \"[[Black Lives Matter#\"White Lives Matter\"|White Lives Matter]]\" and \"[[Identity Evropa#Views|You will not replace us!]]\" with his fellow torch-bearing protestors on the first day. On the second day he beat up a [[transgender]] woman named [[Emily Gorcenski]] with a modified version of the [[Confederate flag]] which incorporated the neo-Nazi [[Black Sun (occult symbol)|Schwarze Sonne]] (Black Sun) symbol in the center, even bragging about the beating in private chats in which he said \"So to sum it up what I did Friday, dropped kicked that tranny that made video crying\", \"Today cracked 3 skulls open with virtually no damage to myself\", and \"I drop kicked Emily gorcenski\". Pistolis had promoted the Unite the Right rally on Twitter under the account of @Gopnik_Gestapo, and posted an image of a car running over a left-winger with the caption \"Good Night, Left Side\". He also mocked the death of [[Heather Heyer]] calling her \"a fat cunt who died of a heart attack. She wasn't even in the way of the car\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8KhAsRJhxeI|title=He's a proud neo-Nazi, Charlottesville attacker \u2013 and a U.S. Marine|last=ProPublica|date=May 11, 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/atomwaffen-division-hate-group-active-duty-militaryofficially|title=Ranks of Notorious Hate Group Include Active-Duty Military|work=Propublica|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Although Pistolis denied that he attended the rally or committed an act of violence, he was investigated by the Marine Corps and was court-martialed in June 2018 for disobeying orders and for making false statements.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/vasilios-pistolis-imprisoned-marine-hate-groups|title=U.S. Marine to Be Imprisoned Over Involvement With Hate Groups|work=Propublica|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Incidents averted===\nIn August 2019, James Patrick Reardon of [[New Middleton, Ohio]] was arrested by local police on charges of telecommunications harassment and aggravated menacing after an [[Instagram]] posting appeared to threaten violent action against the Jewish Community Center synagogue of [[Youngstown, Ohio]]. Reardon had appeared in a 2017 [[National Geographic]] documentary about the [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], in which he identified himself as a [[white nationalist]] and a member of the alt-right. Other posts on Reardon's Instagram account featured images of Reardon shooting weapons, anti-semitic comments and white nationalist material. A search of Reardon's home found an arsenal of weapons and ammunition, including knives and two assault rifles, along with bulletproof armor and a gas mask. Reardon's bail was set for $200,000, and the judge ruled that if he made bail, he would be subject to house arrest with no work privileges, and random home and computer searches and drug testing. He would also be ordered to avoid social media and stay 500 feet away from any Jewish places of worship or community centers.<ref>Andone, Dakin; Vera, Amir; and McLaughlin, Eliott C. (August 19, 2019) [https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/19/us/youngstown-jewish-center-unite-the-right/index.html \"Man accused of threatening an Ohio Jewish center declared himself a white nationalist in a documentary, police say\"] [[CNN]]</ref><ref>Krakow, Morgan (August 18, 2019) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/18/self-described-white-nationalist-with-large-arsenal-arrested-threatening-jewish-center-police-say/ \"Self-described white nationalist with large arsenal arrested for threatening a Jewish center, police say\"] ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref>\n\n== Reactions ==\nThe alt-right presented \"a unique set of challenges\" to journalists, progressives, and conservatives.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=3}}\nThe political scientist [[George Haley|George Hawley]] suggested that the alt-right may pose a greater threat to [[progressivism]] than the mainstream conservative movement.{{sfn|Hawley|2016|p=69}} Hawley was of the view that, because of its use of novel tactics not previously used by the far-right, \"the Alt-Right represents something genuinely new on the American political scene\".{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=11}} Lyons stated that the alt-right \"helped revitalize White nationalist and male supremacist politics in the United States\",{{sfn|Lyons|2017|p=17}} while according to Niewert, the alt-right gave white nationalism \"a fresh new life, rewired for the twenty-first century\".{{sfn|Niewert|2017|p=220}} Kelly noted that it was \"important not to overstate the numbers of the alt-right, nor their power as a voting bloc\", but that their success could be measured \"in terms of their ever-increasing dissemination of extreme right-wing ideals and their ability to project an updated rhetoric of anti-left antagonism into the Overton window of acceptable political discourse.\"{{sfn|Kelly|2017|p=76}}\n\nA poll by [[ABC News]] and ''[[The Washington Post]]'' found that 10% of respondents supported the alt-right, to 50% who opposed it.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=313}} An [[Ipsos]] and [[Reuters]] poll found 6% of respondents supported the movement.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=313}} Such polls indicate that while millions of Americans are supportive of the alt-right's message, they remain a clear minority.{{sfn|Atkinson|2018|p=313}} Gray suggested that the alt-right may have benefited from the manner in which\u2014in the years building up to its appearance\u2014progressives often attacked the Tea Party movement and other right-wingers by accusing them of racism. He suggested that this left many right-wingers with the impression that they would be accused of racism \"regardless of how near or far they are from the centre\" and that this made them more willing to listen to the alt-right's message.{{sfn|Gray|2018|p=146}}\n\nIn 2018, the documentary film ''Alt-Right: Age of Rage'' was released. Directed by [[Adam Bhala Lough]], it included interviews with Spencer and Taylor as well as with anti-fascist activists devoted to combatting the alt-right.<ref>{{cite article |last=DeFore |first=John |title='Alt-Right: Age of Rage': Film Review |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 9, 2018 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/alt-right-age-rage-1093400 |accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite article |last=Robertson |first=Adi |title=Alt-Right: Age of Rage is a snapshot of one of 2017's darkest moments |date=March 14, 2018 |website=The Verge |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/14/17113514/alt-right-age-of-rage-antifa-film-review-sxsw-2018 |accessdate=March 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to the alt-right ===\n{{Main|Responses to the alt-right}}\n\n[[File:Trump is Alt-Right with us. A protest group (I think) (32420565055).jpg|thumb|right|\"Trump is Alt-Right with Us.\" Anti-Trump protesters highlight what they regard as his links to the alt-right and to historical fascism by dressing as Hitler and Mussolini.]]\n\nOpponents of the alt-right have not reached a consensus on how to deal with it.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=160}} Some opponents emphasized \"calling out\" tactics, labelling the alt-right with terms like \"racist\", \"sexist\", \"homophobic\", and \"white supremacist\" in the belief that doing so would scare people away from it.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=3\u20134}} Many commentators urged journalists not to refer to the alt-right by its chosen name, but rather with terms like \"neo-Nazi\".{{sfn|Kelly|2017|p=68}} There was much discussion within U.S. public discourse as to how to avoid the \"normalization\" of the alt-right.{{sfn|Kelly|2017|p=69}} The activist group Stop Normalizing, which opposes the [[normalization (sociology)|normalization]] of terms like alt-right, developed the \"Stop Normalizing Alt Right\" [[Google Chrome extension|Chrome extension]]. The extension went viral shortly after the release of Stop Normalizing's website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/stop-normalizing-alt-righ/cpbldecoiaaphkphaacgcjkajgfbibgi |title=Stop Normalizing Alt Right |website=chrome.google.com|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> The extension changes the term \"alt-right\" on webpages to \"white supremacy\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2016/11/22/stop-normalizing-alt-right-chrome-extension/ |title=Timely browser extension replaces 'alt-right' with 'white supremacy' |last=Hinchliffe |first=Emma |website=Mashable|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/new-chrome-extension-changes-alt-right-white-supremacy-n689881 |title=Chrome extension changes 'alt-right' to 'white supremacy' |newspaper=NBC News|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alt-right-chrome-extension-stop-normalising-hate-white-supremacy-neo-nazi-a7445671.html |title=Chrome extension changes 'alt-right' to 'white supremacy' |date=November 29, 2016 |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> The extension and group were founded by a New York-based advertising and media professional under the [[pseudonym]] George Zola.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/google-chrome-extension-replaces-alt-right-with-white-supremacy_us_583c6106e4b09b60560157b6 |title=Google Chrome Extension Replaces 'Alt-Right' With 'White Supremacy' |last=Workneh |first=Lilly |date=November 28, 2016 |website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSome on the political right, including Yiannopoulos, suggest that the alt-right's appeal would be diffused if society accepted many of its less extreme demands, including curbing political correctness and ending mass immigration.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=160}} Yiannopoulos added that, as part of such an approach, the left should cease holding different social groups to different standards of behavior. He noted that if the left wanted to continue using identity politics as the basis of much of its mobilization, it would have to accept [[white identity politics]] as a permanent fixture of the political landscape.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=160}} Similarly, in highlighting the commonalities between alt-right and \"left-identitarian\" forms of identity politics, Gray suggested the alt-right's presence might encourage \"the intersectional Left and its allies\" to increasingly critique the theoretical basis on which their own identity politics is built.{{sfn|Gray|2018|p=153}} Other commentators, like the conservative [[David Frum]], have suggested that if issues like immigration policy were discussed more openly in public discourse, then the alt-right would no longer be able to monopolize them.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=164}}\n\nSome opponents sought to undermine the alt-right's stereotype of leftists as being devoid of humor and joy by using its own tactics of humor and irony against it. For instance, when alt-rightists became angry or upset, some of their opponents described them as \"snowflakes\" who were being \"triggered\".{{sfn|Wendling|2018|pp=221\u2013222}} Anti-fascist activists also adopted the alt-right's use of pranks; on several occasions they publicized events in which they were purportedly meeting to destroy Confederate monuments or gravestones. Alt-rightists mobilized to publicly defend these sites, only to find that no such anti-fascist event was happening at all.{{sfn|Wendling|2018|p=221}} Within feminist circles, the alt-right's desired future was repeatedly compared to the [[Republic of Gilead]], the fictional dystopia in [[Margaret Atwood]]'s ''[[The Handmaid's Tale]]'' (1985) and its [[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|2017 television adaptation]].{{sfn|Marghitu|Johnson|2018|p=184}}\n\n[[File:Charlottesville \"Unite the Right\" Rally (35780272084).jpg|thumb|left|Counter-protesters at the 2017 Unite the Right rally.]]\n\nVarious opponents have also employed doxing, publicly revealing the identities and addresses of alt-rightists, many of whom had previously acted anonymously.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=166}} This tactic discourages individuals from involving themselves in alt-right activities to begin with, as they fear that should they be outed as alt-rightists they might face repercussions such as job loss, social ostracization, or violence.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=168}} From 2016 onward, some anti-fascist opponents of the alt-right also resorted to physical confrontation and violence against the movement.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=169}} On Trump's inauguration day, for example, a masked anti-fascist punched Spencer in the face when he was talking to reporters; the footage was widely shared online.{{sfnm|1a1=Hawley|1y=2017|1p=169|2a1=Wendling|2y=2018|2pp=2\u20133}} Hawley noted that this tactic could be counter-productive to the anti-alt-right case, as it reinforces the narrative that alt-rightists peacefully engaging in their constitutionally-protected right to free speech were being victimized.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|pp=169\u2013170}}\n\nOther commentators have called for more vigorous policing of the web by governments and companies to deal with the alt-right.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=161}} If denied access to mainstream social media outlets, the alt-right would be restricted to far-right online venues like Stormfront, where it would be isolated and ignored from those not already committed to its cause.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=163}} Many in the alt-right concur that denying it access to social media would have a devastating effect on its ability to proselytize.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=161}} It has however been suggested that such censorship could backfire, as it would play into the alt-right narrative that those campaigning for white interests were being marginalized by the establishment, thus aiding the movement's recruitment.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=164}} Suppressing the alt-right in this manner would also set a precedent which could be repeated for other groups in future, including leftist ones.{{sfn|Hawley|2017|p=165}} Phillips and Yi argued that such leftist attempts to prevent alt-right speech reflected an \"authoritarian shift\" which was becoming \"increasingly hegemonic\" within the American Left and that endorsed the view that \"limiting or preventing the public speech of historically privileged groups (typically, whites, males) is acceptable until power relations are equalized.\"{{sfn|Phillips|Yi|2018|p=226}}\n\n== \"Alt-left\" ==\n{{anchor|Alt-left}}\nAfter the murder of a counter-protester at the Unite the Right Rally, in a press conference Trump stated that there was \"blame on both sides\" for the violence, stating that some of the counter-protesters were part of the \"very, very violent ... alt-left\".{{refn|<ref>Shear, Michael D. and Haberman, Maggie (August 15, 2017). [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/15/us/politics/trump-press-conference-charlottesville.html \"A Combative Trump Criticizes 'Alt-Left' Groups in Charlottesville\"], ''[[The New York Times]].''</ref><ref>Meghan Keneally, [http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trump-lashes-alt-left-charlottesville-fine-people-sides/story?id=49235032 \"Trump lashes out at 'alt-left' in Charlottesville, says 'fine people on both sides'\"], ''ABC News'', August 15, 2017</ref><ref>Andrew Rafferty, [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-defends-all-sides-comment-n793001 \"Trump Says 'Alt-Left' Shares Blame for Charlottesville Rally Violence\"],''NBC News'', August 15, 2017.</ref><ref>Harriet Alexander, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/15/alt-left-donald-trump-said-violent-charlottesville/ \"What is the 'alt Left' that Donald Trump said was 'very violent' in Charlottesville?\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', August 16, 2017.</ref>}} Various experts pointed out that the [[neologism]] \"alt-left\" was neither created nor adopted by any members of the progressive left.<ref>{{cite news |title=What's the 'alt-left'? Experts say it's a 'made-up term' |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/08/16/politics/what-is-alt-left/index.html |author=Joe Sterling |author2=Nicole Chavez |website=CNN |publisher=Time Warner |date=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What Is The Alt-Left? Trump Pinned The Charlottesville Violence On Them, Too |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/what-is-the-alt-left-trump-pinned-the-charlottesville-violence-on-them-too-76849 |author=Chris Tognotti |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=August 15, 2017}}</ref> The term \"alt-left\" has been criticized as a label that was not coined by the group it purports to describe, rather by its political opponents as a smear.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why the Alt-Center Is a Problem, Too |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/03/why-the-alt-center-is-a-problem-too.html |author=Eric Levitz |newspaper=[[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]] |publisher=New York Media, LLC |date=March 3, 2017 |accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the 'alt-left': The GOP's response to its alt-right problem |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/12/01/meet-the-alt-left-the-gops-response-to-its-alt-right-problem/ |author=Aaron Blake |newspaper=The Washington Post |publisher=Nash Holdings LLC |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=August 16, 2017}}</ref> The historian [[Timothy D. Snyder]] stated that {{\"'}}alt-right' is a term ... meant to provide a fresh label that would sound more attractive than 'Nazi,' 'neo-Nazi,' 'white supremacist,' or 'white nationalist.' With 'alt-left' it's a different story. There is no group that labels itself that way\".<ref name=\"Lee\"/> The scholar of public affairs Thomas J. Main commented on the alt-right by saying: \"They don't think blacks and Jews should have equal rights. On the left, there is nothing analogous\".<ref name=\"Lee\"/> According to [[Mark Pitcavage]], an analyst at the [[Anti-Defamation League]], the term was invented to suggest a [[false equivalence]] between the alt-right and their opponents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/15/us/politics/alt-left-alt-right-glossary.html |title=Alt-Right, Alt-Left, Antifa: A Glossary of Extremist Language |work=[[The New York Times]] |last1=Stack |first1=Liam |date=August 15, 2017 |accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref> Since 2016, the term \"alt-left\" has also been used derisively to describe political views that lie within the [[Left-wing politics|left]], as well as individuals perceived as adhering to those views, particularly within political discussions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/term-alt-left-came|title=How the term 'alt-left' came to be|author=|publisher=PBS News Hour|date=16 August 2017|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/03/why-the-alt-left-is-a-problem|title=Why the Alt-Left Is a Problem, Too|author=James Wolcott|publisher=Vanity Fair|date=March 2017|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Groypers ==\nDuring October and November 2019, Turning Point USA launched the 'Culture War' college tour of speaking events with appearances from many conservatives such as [[Donald Trump Jr.]], [[Lara Trump]] and [[Kimberly Guilfoyle]]. These events were frequently targeted by homophobic and antisemitic members of the alt- and far-right who consider TPUSA to be too mainstream and not sufficiently conservative. Concerted efforts were made by this group, led by [[Nick Fuentes]], to ask leading questions during the Q&A sections on controversial topics such as Israel and LGBTQ issues in order to challenge the extent of the speakers' views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/11/11/20948317/alt-right-donald-trump-jr-conservative-tpusa-yaf-racism-antisemitism|title=Why alt-right trolls shouted down Donald Trump Jr.|last=Coaston|first=Jane|date=2019-11-11|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112152101/https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/11/11/20948317/alt-right-donald-trump-jr-conservative-tpusa-yaf-racism-antisemitism|archive-date=November 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These members are called Groypers.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n* [[Angry white male]]\n* [[The Alt-Right Playbook]]\n* [[Blood and Soil]]\n* [[Far-left politics]], political views that lie at the opposite end of the political spectrum\n* [[Identitarian movement]], parallel movement in Europe\n* [[Neo-integralism]], parallel movement in Brazil\n* [[Neo-Nazism]]\n* [[Neo-nationalism]]\n* [[New Right]]\n* [[Racism in the United States]]\n* [[Right-wing authoritarianism]]\n* [[Right-wing terrorism]]\n* [[Vigilante#Vigilante conduct|Vigilantism]]\n\n== References ==\n'''Informational notes'''\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n''' Citations'''\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"FarRight\">\n*{{cite news |last1=Stack |first1=Liam |title=Alt-Right, Alt-Left, Antifa: A Glossary of Extremist Language |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/15/us/politics/alt-left-alt-right-glossary.html |accessdate=March 3, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=August 15, 2017 |quote=The 'alt-right' is a racist, '''far-right''' movement based on an ideology of white nationalism and anti-Semitism.}}\n*{{cite news |title=Explained: Alt-right, alt-light and militias in the US |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/09/explained-alt-alt-light-militias-170924084455057.html |accessdate=March 3, 2019 |work=Al Jazeera |date=October 12, 2017|quote=The alt-right is a loosely knit coalition of '''far-right''' groups that includes populists, white supremacists, white nationalists, neo-Confederates and neo-Nazis.}}\n*{{cite web |title=Alt-Right |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/ideology/alt-right |website=Southern Poverty Law Center |accessdate=February 10, 2018 |language=en |quote=The Alternative Right, commonly known as the Alt-Right, is a set of '''far-right''' ideologies, groups and individuals whose core belief is that 'white identity' is under attack by multicultural forces using 'political correctness' and 'social justice' to undermine white people and 'their' civilization.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Berger |first1=J. M. |title=Trump Is the Glue That Binds the Far Right |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2018/10/trump-alt-right-twitter/574219/ |accessdate=March 3, 2019 |work=The Atlantic |date=October 29, 2018 |quote=The alt-right bloc synchronizes activity that starts on the far-right edge of mainstream conservatism and continues through the far reaches of genocidal white supremacy.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Pitofsky |first1=Marina |title=What is the alt-right? And how is it using social media to spread its message? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2018/07/23/alt-right-philosophy-white-identity-civil-rights/800232002/ |accessdate=March 3, 2019 |work=USA TODAY |date=July 28, 2018 |language=en |quote=The alt-right is a collection of '''far-right''' groups and people dedicated to \"white ethnonationalism\" in Western civilization, or the preservation of a white populace in Western countries.}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite news |last=Wallace-Wells |first=Benjamin |title=Is the Alt-Right for real? |url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/benjamin-wallace-wells/is-the-alt-right-for-real |work=The New Yorker |date=May 5,